Subject: [sfraves] NRR: Bill Hicks censored appearance from 15 yrs. ago on Letterman
 finally gets aired

http://www.joketribe.com/video/The.Unseen.Bill.Hicks.Appearance.On.Letterman.php

More than 15 years ago, under fear of retaliation from The Religious 
Right, David Letterman chose to not air a stand-up act from the late 
Bill Hicks, who died of cancer not long after.

Bill Hicks, a comedian who described himself as "Chomsky with dick 
jokes," opens with a joke about having a new TV show where they "hunt 
and kill Billy Ray Cyrus." He also takes stabs at the pro-lifers as well 
as Easter. So it's not clear what Letterman feared would be the most 
controversial. But for the highly delayed broadcast he was highly 
apologetic, airing the act in it's entirety and stating to Mary Hicks, 
Bill's mom, whom he invited on the show to introduce the clip, "Let me 
again apologize for the heartache and sadness my decision caused your 
family."


--

On Sun, Feb 1, 2009 at 10:51 PM, J.C. <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu> wrote:

>
> http://www.joketribe.com/video/The.Unseen.Bill.Hicks.Appearance.On.Letterman.php
>
> More than 15 years ago, under fear of retaliation from The Religious Right,
> David Letterman chose to not air a stand-up act from the late Bill Hicks,
> who died of cancer not long after.
>
> Bill Hicks, a comedian who described himself as "Chomsky with dick jokes,"
> opens with a joke about having a new TV show where they "hunt and kill Billy
> Ray Cyrus." He also takes stabs at the pro-lifers as well as Easter. So it's
> not clear what Letterman feared would be the most controversial. But for the
> highly delayed broadcast he was highly apologetic, airing the act in it's
> entirety and stating to Mary Hicks, Bill's mom, whom he invited on the show
> to introduce the clip, "Let me again apologize for the heartache and sadness
> my decision caused your family."
>

Subject: [sfraves] NRR: How much do you pay in income tax?

Not sure how many folks are friends with Apollo on facebook, but here's a link 
he shared over there:
http://www.toomuchonline.org/tmweekly.html

At the bottom in the sidebar is this interesting stat:
Stat of the Week

How low can taxes on America's rich go? This low: The IRS revealed last week 
that America.s 400 highest-income taxpayers averaged $263 million each in 2006 
and paid just 17.2 percent of that, or $45 million, in federal income tax. In 
1992, America's 400 richest averaged only $46.8 million in income and paid 26.4 
percent of that in tax.

Equitable?  Rightfully gotten?

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: How much do you pay in income tax?

Seems like they're paying their fair share. Those percentages aren't 
that low if you consider America's corporate tax compared to other 
countries. It's like you complain about the wealthy's "low" tax-rate, 
but what is your suggestion of a fair tax-rate for the fortunate 400? Is 
50% fair? is 75% fair? I'm serious, what is your suggestion?

People should be focusing on the real issues that are creating wealth 
disparity in the USA, such as the endless availability of cheap foreign 
labor, the corrupt SEC and it's hedge-funds, or the enormous tax-burden 
(deficit) that is the occupation of Iraq (nobody wants to talk about that).

The disparity of wealth and the health of the economy won't be solved by 
taxing the rich more. Especially when the taxes will just be wasted on 
something like the Iraq.

// dreamdust

I just sit here at my computer and think oh my god I had so much fun.
I can't even count how many parties I went to since I was 16 yo and how man=
y different DJs I heard live. How many different people I met from so many =
different cities and countries. I remember so many different locations for =
parties and afterparties that its crazy. Those were the most awsome amazing=
 experiences that have changed the way I see the world even for=A0now.=A0I =
can't even explain how much fun that all was. I miss those nights and those=
 weekends and the camp outs and omg that was incredible I am so fucking luc=
ky to have those experiences be a part of my memories. If I could go back a=
nd do it all over again I would. Omg I was so lucky to have gone through th=
at experience and met all those people. I just get lost in my vivid memorie=
s of parties gone by and I miss those feelings that I had when you are surr=
ounded by all your good friends with good vibes and you just feel like this=
 is amazing and how can this all be happening how can life be this
 fantastic how can i be so lucky to have fallen into this autonomous zone w=
hat did I do that was so good that granted me access to this amazing electr=
onic music world and underground culture that is beyond imagination and enc=
ourages the expression of the creative force that is within each of us. Wow=
.. I am in awe of the success of it all and how the novelty ceases to wear o=
ff. And day after day just amazed at how much more I remember as time passe=
s. I just=A0 think to myself oh my god that was so awsome. It's like some a=
mazing dream. Did that all just really happen? Wow. I wanna go on that ride=
 again. I wish I could like take some magic elixer that would make me fall =
asleep and wake up=A0in 1996=A0at a party.
And I would get to experience all those parties over again.=0A=0A=0A

Saturday, February 7th, 2008

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 1st Saturday at The Endup



featuring from Berlin:


MIKE SHANNON

(Cynosure . Plus 8 . Wagon Repair)
(Dumb-Unit . Force Inc . Num . ~scape)

A DJ since age 12, Mike Shannon had been an
integral member of the Canadian techno community
centered out of Montreal and a respected player on
the international scene for over a decade prior to his
recent move to Berlin. Whether it's putting out jackin',
quirky minimal techno and house on his own
Cynosure label, or producing acclaimed music on
some of the world's finest labels such as his recent
Memory Tree album on Plus8, Mike's total submersion
into the techno world is a reflection of his passion
and dedication to sharing great music with the world.



and special guest from Minneapols:


DUSTIN ZAHN - live pa

(Enemy . Drumcode . Droid Recordings . Rekids)

Dustin Zahn's distinctive brand of dark and heady
peak-hour techno has quickly carved him a place
amongst the best in the business. 2008 was a huge
year for this talented young artist, and with a stellar
string of releases on Drumcode, Droid Recordings,
and his own Enemy Records, 2009 shows no signs
of slowing.



with [KONTROL] residents:


NIKOLA BAYTALA  (S.W.A.T. . Robsoul . Junior Boys Own)
http://www.myspace.com/nikolaswat

CRAIG KUNA  (Platform . ESDJCO)
http://www.myspace.com/craig1

ALLAND BYALLO  (Nightlight . Auralism . Leibe*Detail)
http://www.myspace.com/alland

SAMMY D  (Classic . Dirtybird . Utensil)
http://www.myspace.com/sammydoyle


____________________________________________________


The ENDUP
401 6th St @ Harrison, SF
10pm - 6am / 21+ / $15 til 2am
http://www.theendup.com

FREE before 11pm!

___________________________________________________


MIKE SHANNON

(bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)

It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's recently
crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third full
length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's not
just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno community,
it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing behind
a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
the scene.

Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of Kitchener,
Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds from
across Europe.

Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers and
artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure in
1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed into
highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such as
Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.

For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists who
possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his own
work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under his
own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven by
a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of chilled-out
Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.

Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers having
taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
personally.

____________________________________________________


DUSTIN ZAHN

After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin, Dustin
began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met future-partner
Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained to
him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he was
talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks and
won just as much respect as he did with his productions.

In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next level.
They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.

A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman in
2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind, Compound,
GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The Attack
People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the mind
and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When not
in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.

In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains" on
Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a name
the techno world will be hearing much more of.


===> LINKS:

Dustin Zahn's website:
http://www.enemyrecords.com/

Dustin Zahn on MySpace (with music samples):
http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn

Dustin Zahn's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/dustin%20zahn

> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of Kitchener,
> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
> from
> across Europe.
>
> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
> and
> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure in
> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed into
> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such as
> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>
> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists who
> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his own
> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
> his
> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven by
> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
> chilled-out
> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>
> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
> having
> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
> personally.
>
>
> ===> LINKS:
>
> Mike Shannon/Cynosure on MySpace:
> http://www.myspace.com/cynrecordings
>
> Mike Shannon's discography:
> http://www.discogs.com/artist/Mike%20Shannon
>
> Mike Shannon's website:
> http://www.cynosure-recordings.com/
>
> Review of Memory Tree w/ music samples:
> http://www.littlewhiteearbuds.com/mike-shannon-memory-tree/
>
>
> ===> MUSIC:
>
> Mike Shannon @ Watergate, Berlin  (streaming)
> http://www.cynbookings.com/?p=6#artistaudio
>
> Mike Shannon - Live @ DEMF - Underground Stage  05.28.05
> http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Mike_Shannon_@_DEMF_2005.mp3
>
>
> ===> VIDEO:
>
> Mike Shannon @ Cityfox, Zurich
> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9OkJ-yKst0
>
> Interview with Mike Shannon
> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBTYzTjZIX8
>
>
> ____________________________________________________
>
>
> DUSTIN ZAHN
>
> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
> Dustin
> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
> future-partner
> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
> to
> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
> was
> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks and
> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>
> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next level.
> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>
> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman in
> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
> Compound,
> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
> Attack
> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
> mind
> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When not
> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>
> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
> on
> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
> name
> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>
>
> ===> LINKS:
>
> Dustin Zahn's website:
> http://www.enemyrecords.com/
>
> Dustin Zahn on MySpace (with music samples):
> http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn
>
> Dustin Zahn's discography:
> http://www.discogs.com/artist/dustin%20zahn
>

>> integral member of the Canadian techno community
>> centered out of Montreal and a respected player on
>> the international scene for over a decade prior to his
>> recent move to Berlin. Whether it's putting out jackin',
>> quirky minimal techno and house on his own
>> Cynosure label, or producing acclaimed music on
>> some of the world's finest labels such as his recent
>> Memory Tree album on Plus8, Mike's total submersion

>> ___________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> MIKE SHANNON
>>
>> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
>>
>> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
>> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
>> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
>> recently
>> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
>> full
>> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
>> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
>> not
>> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
>> community,
>> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
>> behind
>> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
>> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
>> the scene.
>>
>> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
>> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
>> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
>> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
>> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
>> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
>> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
>> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
>> Kitchener,
>> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
>> from
>> across Europe.
>>
>> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
>> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
>> and
>> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
>> in
>> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
>> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
>> into
>> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
>> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
>> as
>> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
>> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
>> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
>> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>>
>> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
>> who
>> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
>> own
>> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
>> his
>> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
>> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
>> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
>> by
>> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
>> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
>> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
>> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
>> chilled-out
>> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>>
>> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
>> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
>> having
>> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
>> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
>> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
>> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
>> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
>> personally.
>>
>>

>>
>> DUSTIN ZAHN
>>
>> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
>> Dustin
>> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
>> future-partner
>> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
>> to
>> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
>> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
>> was
>> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
>> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
>> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
>> and
>> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>>
>> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
>> level.
>> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
>> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
>> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>>
>> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
>> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
>> in
>> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
>> Compound,
>> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
>> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
>> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
>> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
>> Attack
>> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
>> mind
>> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
>> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
>> not
>> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
>> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>>
>> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
>> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
>> on
>> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
>> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
>> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
>> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
>> name
>> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>>

>>> MIKE SHANNON
>>>
>>> (Cynosure . Plus 8 . Wagon Repair)
>>> (Dumb-Unit . Force Inc . Num . ~scape)
>>>
>>> A DJ since age 12, Mike Shannon had been an
>>> integral member of the Canadian techno community
>>> centered out of Montreal and a respected player on
>>> the international scene for over a decade prior to his
>>> recent move to Berlin. Whether it's putting out jackin',
>>> quirky minimal techno and house on his own
>>> Cynosure label, or producing acclaimed music on
>>> some of the world's finest labels such as his recent
>>> Memory Tree album on Plus8, Mike's total submersion
>>> into the techno world is a reflection of his passion
>>> and dedication to sharing great music with the world.
>>>
>>>
>>>
>>> and special guest from Minneapols:
>>>
>>>
>>> DUSTIN ZAHN - live pa
>>>
>>> (Enemy . Drumcode . Droid Recordings . Rekids)
>>>
>>> Dustin Zahn's distinctive brand of dark and heady
>>> peak-hour techno has quickly carved him a place
>>> amongst the best in the business. 2008 was a huge
>>> year for this talented young artist, and with a stellar
>>> string of releases on Drumcode, Droid Recordings,
>>> and his own Enemy Records, 2009 shows no signs
>>> of slowing.
>>>
>>>
>>>
>>> with [KONTROL] residents:
>>>
>>>

>>> ___________________________________________________
>>>
>>>
>>> MIKE SHANNON
>>>
>>> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
>>>
>>> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
>>> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
>>> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
>>> recently
>>> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
>>> full
>>> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
>>> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
>>> not
>>> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
>>> community,
>>> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
>>> behind
>>> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
>>> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
>>> the scene.
>>>
>>> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
>>> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
>>> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
>>> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
>>> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
>>> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
>>> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
>>> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
>>> Kitchener,
>>> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
>>> from
>>> across Europe.
>>>
>>> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
>>> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
>>> and
>>> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
>>> in
>>> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
>>> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
>>> into
>>> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
>>> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
>>> as
>>> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
>>> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
>>> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
>>> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>>>
>>> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
>>> who
>>> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
>>> own
>>> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
>>> his
>>> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
>>> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
>>> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
>>> by
>>> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
>>> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
>>> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
>>> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
>>> chilled-out
>>> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>>>
>>> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
>>> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
>>> having
>>> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
>>> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
>>> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
>>> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
>>> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
>>> personally.
>>>
>>>
>>> ===> LINKS:
>>>
>>> Mike Shannon/Cynosure on MySpace:
>>> http://www.myspace.com/cynrecordings
>>>
>>> Mike Shannon's discography:
>>> http://www.discogs.com/artist/Mike%20Shannon
>>>
>>> Mike Shannon's website:
>>> http://www.cynosure-recordings.com/
>>>
>>> Review of Memory Tree w/ music samples:
>>> http://www.littlewhiteearbuds.com/mike-shannon-memory-tree/
>>>
>>>

>>> http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Mike_Shannon_@_DEMF_2005.mp3
>>>
>>>
>>> ===> VIDEO:
>>>
>>> Mike Shannon @ Cityfox, Zurich
>>> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9OkJ-yKst0
>>>
>>> Interview with Mike Shannon
>>> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBTYzTjZIX8
>>>
>>>
>>> ____________________________________________________
>>>
>>>
>>> DUSTIN ZAHN
>>>
>>> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
>>> Dustin
>>> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
>>> future-partner
>>> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
>>> to
>>> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
>>> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
>>> was
>>> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
>>> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
>>> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
>>> and
>>> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>>>
>>> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
>>> level.
>>> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
>>> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
>>> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>>>
>>> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
>>> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
>>> in
>>> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
>>> Compound,
>>> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
>>> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
>>> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
>>> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
>>> Attack
>>> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
>>> mind
>>> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
>>> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
>>> not
>>> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
>>> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>>>
>>> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
>>> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
>>> on
>>> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
>>> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
>>> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
>>> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
>>> name
>>> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>>>
>>>
>>> ===> LINKS:
>>>
>>> Dustin Zahn's website:
>>> http://www.enemyrecords.com/
>>>
>>> Dustin Zahn on MySpace (with music samples):
>>> http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn
>>>
>>> Dustin Zahn's discography:
>>> http://www.discogs.com/artist/dustin%20zahn
>>>

From: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Mike Shannon (Plus 8) +  Dustin Zahn live (Drumcode)

With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event (that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.

To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then! 

Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.

I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing things at the wall until something sticks.

-George

>> ___________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> MIKE SHANNON
>>
>> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
>>
>> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
>> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
>> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
>> recently
>> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
>> full
>> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
>> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
>> not
>> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
>> community,
>> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
>> behind
>> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
>> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
>> the scene.
>>
>> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
>> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
>> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
>> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
>> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
>> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
>> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
>> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
>> Kitchener,
>> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
>> from
>> across Europe.
>>
>> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
>> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
>> and
>> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
>> in
>> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
>> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
>> into
>> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
>> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
>> as
>> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
>> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
>> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
>> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>>
>> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
>> who
>> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
>> own
>> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
>> his
>> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
>> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
>> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
>> by
>> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
>> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
>> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
>> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
>> chilled-out
>> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>>
>> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
>> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
>> having
>> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
>> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
>> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
>> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
>> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
>> personally.
>>
>>

>> ____________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> DUSTIN ZAHN
>>
>> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
>> Dustin
>> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
>> future-partner
>> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
>> to
>> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
>> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
>> was
>> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
>> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
>> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
>> and
>> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>>
>> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
>> level.
>> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
>> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
>> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>>
>> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
>> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
>> in
>> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
>> Compound,
>> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
>> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
>> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
>> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
>> Attack
>> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
>> mind
>> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
>> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
>> not
>> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
>> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>>
>> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
>> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
>> on
>> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
>> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
>> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
>> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
>> name
>> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>>
>>

--0015174c3d166b50eb0462474212
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

When we look back at the beginnings of DJing and EDM, and compare it with
the vinyl-only purists of the present, it's a complete paradox!

DJs and makers of electronic music were being railed back then for creating
and playing stuff that wasn't "real" music.  But hey, they embraced the
artform, and eventually brought it to the masses, and now it has a
celebrated history from it's early beginnings to the present.  If the
visionary thinkers of the dub sound systems of Jamaica and New York didn't
exist, what would the DJ be today?  What about dj Pierre and his Roland
tb-303, and then the explosion of the Acid House parties in the UK come the
late 80s, would the full moons on Bonny Doon, and later massives at homebase
have flourished?  Would the Playa be filled with dozens of sound systems
playing every type of electronic music the mind can imagine?

As connisseurs of electronic dance music, isn't it in our nature to push the
envelope, and look to technology to spread new noises and artforms?  Or have
we become so caught up in ourselves that we're content with the status quo?

> BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh bra
> if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in the
> last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.
>
> To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then!
>
> Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun paying
> $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom of
> records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having
> access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10
> years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every gig
> while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All
> I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record
> purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and
> ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.
>
> I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but
> to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is just
> retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me about a party
> is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I
> guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing things at the wall until
> something sticks.
>
> -George
>
>

> >> Memory Tree album on Plus8, Mike's total submersion

> >> ___________________________________________________
> >>
> >>
> >> MIKE SHANNON
> >>
> >> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
> >>
> >> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself
> on
> >> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
> >> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
> >> recently
> >> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
> >> full
> >> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export -
> Richie
> >> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
> >> not
> >> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
> >> community,
> >> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
> >> behind
> >> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
> >> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future
> of
> >> the scene.
> >>
> >> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
> >> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
> >> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs.
> From
> >> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part
> to
> >> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R.,
> Juan
> >> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in
> his
> >> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno,
> he
> >> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
> >> Kitchener,
> >> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
> >> from
> >> across Europe.
> >>
> >> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
> >> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
> >> and
> >> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
> >> in
> >> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the
> more
> >> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
> >> into
> >> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile
> of
> >> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
> >> as
> >> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their
> distinctive
> >> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
> >> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international
> artists
> >> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
> >>
> >> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
> >> who
> >> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
> >> own
> >> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
> >> his
> >> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
> >> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and
> never
> >> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
> >> by
> >> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
> >> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that
> cemented
> >> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
> >> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
> >> chilled-out
> >> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
> >>
> >> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another
> chapter
> >> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
> >> having
> >> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
> >> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
> >> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
> >> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
> >> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
> >> personally.
> >>
> >>

> >> ____________________________________________________
> >>
> >>
> >> DUSTIN ZAHN
> >>
> >> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
> >> Dustin
> >> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
> >> future-partner
> >> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian
> explained
> >> to
> >> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
> >> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
> >> was
> >> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this
> was
> >> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
> >> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
> >> and
> >> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
> >>
> >> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
> >> level.
> >> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
> >> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
> >> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
> >>
> >> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal,
> dark,
> >> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
> >> in
> >> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
> >> Compound,
> >> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from
> many
> >> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
> >> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
> >> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
> >> Attack
> >> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
> >> mind
> >> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets
> which
> >> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
> >> not
> >> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
> >> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
> >>
> >> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons
> of
> >> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The
> Chains"
> >> on
> >> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on
> his
> >> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire,
> as
> >> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
> >> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
> >> name
> >> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
> >>
> >>
> >> ===> LINKS:
> >>

> >> http://www.enemyrecords.com/

From: Ben Haus <benhaus@gmail.com>
To: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
Cc: Greg Bird <bird415@gmail.com>; SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Friday, February 6, 2009 2:08:23 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Mike Shannon (Plus 8) +  Dustin Zahn live (Drumcode)

When we look back at the beginnings of DJing and EDM, and compare it with the vinyl-only purists of the present, it's a complete paradox!  

DJs and makers of electronic music were being railed back then for creating and playing stuff that wasn't "real" music.  But hey, they embraced the artform, and eventually brought it to the masses, and now it has a celebrated history from it's early beginnings to the present.  If the visionary thinkers of the dub sound systems of Jamaica and New York didn't exist, what would the DJ be today?  What about dj Pierre and his Roland tb-303, and then the explosion of the Acid House parties in the UK come the late 80s, would the full moons on Bonny Doon, and later massives at homebase have flourished?  Would the Playa be filled with dozens of sound systems playing every type of electronic music the mind can imagine?    

As connisseurs of electronic dance music, isn't it in our nature to push the envelope, and look to technology to spread new noises and artforms?  Or have we become so caught up in ourselves that we're content with the status quo?  




On Fri, Feb 6, 2009 at 1:55 PM, George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com> wrote:

With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event (that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.

To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then!

Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.

I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing things at the wall until something sticks.

-George

>>
>> MIKE SHANNON
>>
>> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
>>
>> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
>> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
>> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
>> recently
>> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
>> full
>> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
>> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
>> not
>> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
>> community,
>> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
>> behind
>> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
>> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
>> the scene.
>>
>> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
>> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
>> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
>> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
>> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
>> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
>> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
>> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
>> Kitchener,
>> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
>> from
>> across Europe.
>>
>> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
>> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
>> and
>> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
>> in
>> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
>> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
>> into
>> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
>> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
>> as
>> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
>> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
>> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
>> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>>
>> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
>> who
>> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
>> own
>> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
>> his
>> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
>> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
>> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
>> by
>> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
>> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
>> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
>> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
>> chilled-out
>> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>>
>> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
>> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
>> having
>> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
>> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
>> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
>> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
>> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
>> personally.
>>
>>
>> ===> LINKS:
>>
>> Mike Shannon/Cynosure on MySpace:
>> http://www.myspace.com/cynrecordings
>>
>> Mike Shannon's discography:
>> http://www.discogs.com/artist/Mike%20Shannon
>>
>> Mike Shannon's website:
>> http://www.cynosure-recordings.com/
>>
>> Review of Memory Tree w/ music samples:
>> http://www.littlewhiteearbuds.com/mike-shannon-memory-tree/
>>
>>
>> ===> MUSIC:
>>
>> Mike Shannon @ Watergate, Berlin  (streaming)
>> http://www.cynbookings.com/?p=6#artistaudio
>>
>> Mike Shannon - Live @ DEMF - Underground Stage  05.28.05
>> http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/Mike_Shannon_@_DEMF_2005.mp3
>>
>>
>> ===> VIDEO:
>>
>> Mike Shannon @ Cityfox, Zurich
>> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=k9OkJ-yKst0
>>
>> Interview with Mike Shannon
>> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBTYzTjZIX8
>>
>>
>> ____________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> DUSTIN ZAHN
>>
>> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
>> Dustin
>> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
>> future-partner
>> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
>> to
>> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
>> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
>> was
>> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
>> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
>> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
>> and
>> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>>
>> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
>> level.
>> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
>> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
>> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>>
>> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
>> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
>> in
>> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
>> Compound,
>> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
>> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
>> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
>> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
>> Attack
>> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
>> mind
>> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
>> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
>> not
>> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
>> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>>
>> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
>> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
>> on
>> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
>> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
>> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
>> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
>> name
>> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>>
>>
>> ===> LINKS:
>>
>> Dustin Zahn's website:
>> http://www.enemyrecords.com/
>>
>> Dustin Zahn on MySpace (with music samples):
>> http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn
>>
>> Dustin Zahn's discography:
>> http://www.discogs.com/artist/dustin%20zahn

On Sat, Feb 7, 2009 at 1:14 AM, George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>wrote:

> Exactly!

> ________________________________
> From: Ben Haus <benhaus@gmail.com>
> To: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
> Cc: Greg Bird <bird415@gmail.com>; SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
> Sent: Friday, February 6, 2009 2:08:23 PM
> Subject: Re: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Mike Shannon (Plus 8) +
>  Dustin Zahn live (Drumcode)
>
> When we look back at the beginnings of DJing and EDM, and compare it with
> the vinyl-only purists of the present, it's a complete paradox!
>
> DJs and makers of electronic music were being railed back then for creating
> and playing stuff that wasn't "real" music.  But hey, they embraced the
> artform, and eventually brought it to the masses, and now it has a
> celebrated history from it's early beginnings to the present.  If the
> visionary thinkers of the dub sound systems of Jamaica and New York didn't
> exist, what would the DJ be today?  What about dj Pierre and his Roland
> tb-303, and then the explosion of the Acid House parties in the UK come the
> late 80s, would the full moons on Bonny Doon, and later massives at homebase
> have flourished?  Would the Playa be filled with dozens of sound systems
> playing every type of electronic music the mind can imagine?
>
> As connisseurs of electronic dance music, isn't it in our nature to push
> the envelope, and look to technology to spread new noises and artforms?  Or
> have we become so caught up in ourselves that we're content with the status
> quo?
>
>
>
>
> On Fri, Feb 6, 2009 at 1:55 PM, George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
> wrote:
>
> With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event (that I
> will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail on this vinyl
> elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am good friends with a
> BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh bra
> if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in the
> last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.
>
> To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then!
>
> Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun paying
> $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom of
> records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having
> access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10
> years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every gig
> while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All
> I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record
> purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and
> ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.
>
> I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but
> to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is just
> retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me about a party
> is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I
> guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing things at the wall until
> something sticks.
>
> -George
>
>

> >> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
> >> in
> >> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
> >> Compound,
> >> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from
> many
> >> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
> >> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
> >> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
> >> Attack
> >> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
> >> mind
> >> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets
> which
> >> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
> >> not
> >> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
> >> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
> >>
> >> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons
> of
> >> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The
> Chains"
> >> on
> >> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on
> his
> >> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire,
> as
> >> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
> >> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
> >> name
> >> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
> >>
> >>
> >> ===> LINKS:
> >>
> >> Dustin Zahn's website:
> >> http://www.enemyrecords.com/

> >> http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn

> >
> > When we look back at the beginnings of DJing and EDM, and compare it with
> > the vinyl-only purists of the present, it's a complete paradox!
> >
> > DJs and makers of electronic music were being railed back then for
> creating
> > and playing stuff that wasn't "real" music.  But hey, they embraced the
> > artform, and eventually brought it to the masses, and now it has a
> > celebrated history from it's early beginnings to the present.  If the
> > visionary thinkers of the dub sound systems of Jamaica and New York
> didn't
> > exist, what would the DJ be today?  What about dj Pierre and his Roland
> > tb-303, and then the explosion of the Acid House parties in the UK come
> the
> > late 80s, would the full moons on Bonny Doon, and later massives at
> homebase
> > have flourished?  Would the Playa be filled with dozens of sound systems
> > playing every type of electronic music the mind can imagine?
> >
> > As connisseurs of electronic dance music, isn't it in our nature to push
> > the envelope, and look to technology to spread new noises and artforms?
>  Or
> > have we become so caught up in ourselves that we're content with the
> status
> > quo?
> >
> >
> >
> >
> > On Fri, Feb 6, 2009 at 1:55 PM, George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com
> >
> > wrote:
> >
> > With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event (that I
> > will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail on this
> vinyl
> > elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am good friends with a
> > BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh
> bra
> > if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in
> the
> > last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.
> >
> > To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then!
> >
> > Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun
> paying
> > $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom
> of
> > records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having
> > access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10
> > years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every
> gig
> > while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.
>  All
> > I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record
> > purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to,
> and
> > ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.
> >
> > I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but

> > is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I

> > something sticks.

> > >>
> > >> (Cynosure . Plus 8 . Wagon Repair)
> > >> (Dumb-Unit . Force Inc . Num . ~scape)
> > >>
> > >> A DJ since age 12, Mike Shannon had been an
> > >> integral member of the Canadian techno community
> > >> centered out of Montreal and a respected player on
> > >> the international scene for over a decade prior to his
> > >> recent move to Berlin. Whether it's putting out jackin',
> > >> quirky minimal techno and house on his own
> > >> Cynosure label, or producing acclaimed music on
> > >> some of the world's finest labels such as his recent
> > >> Memory Tree album on Plus8, Mike's total submersion
> > >> into the techno world is a reflection of his passion
> > >> and dedication to sharing great music with the world.
> > >>

> > >>
> > >> (Enemy . Drumcode . Droid Recordings . Rekids)
> > >>
> > >> Dustin Zahn's distinctive brand of dark and heady
> > >> peak-hour techno has quickly carved him a place
> > >> amongst the best in the business. 2008 was a huge
> > >> year for this talented young artist, and with a stellar
> > >> string of releases on Drumcode, Droid Recordings,
> > >> and his own Enemy Records, 2009 shows no signs
> > >> of slowing.
> > >>

> > >> ___________________________________________________
> > >>
> > >>
> > >> MIKE SHANNON
> > >>
> > >> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
> > >>
> > >> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for
> himself
> > on
> > >> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
> > >> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
> > >> recently
> > >> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
> > >> full
> > >> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export -
> > Richie
> > >> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that
> it's
> > >> not
> > >> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
> > >> community,
> > >> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
> > >> behind
> > >> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
> > >> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future
> > of
> > >> the scene.
> > >>
> > >> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
> > >> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable
> skills
> > >> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs.
> > From
> > >> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part
> > to
> > >> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R.,
> > Juan
> > >> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in
> > his
> > >> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things
> Techno,
> > he
> > >> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
> > >> Kitchener,
> > >> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge
> sounds
> > >> from
> > >> across Europe.
> > >>
> > >> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
> > >> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of
> producers
> > >> and
> > >> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label
> Cynosure
> > >> in
> > >> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the
> > more
> > >> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
> > >> into
> > >> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile
> > of
> > >> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers
> such
> > >> as
> > >> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their
> > distinctive
> > >> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
> > >> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international
> > artists
> > >> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
> > >>
> > >> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising
> artists
> > >> who
> > >> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines
> his
> > >> own
> > >> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or
> under
> > >> his
> > >> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
> > >> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and
> > never
> > >> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily
> proven
> > >> by
> > >> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
> > >> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that
> > cemented
> > >> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
> > >> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
> > >> chilled-out
> > >> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
> > >>
> > >> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another
> > chapter
> > >> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
> > >> having
> > >> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's
> a
> > >> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on
> new
> > >> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the
> new
> > >> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
> > >> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally
> and
> > >> personally.
> > >>
> > >>

> > >> Interview with Mike Shannon
> > >> http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lBTYzTjZIX8

> > >>
> > >> ____________________________________________________
> > >>
> > >>
> > >> DUSTIN ZAHN
> > >>
> > >> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
> > >> Dustin
> > >> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
> > >> future-partner
> > >> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian
> > explained
> > >> to
> > >> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
> > >> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what
> he
> > >> was
> > >> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this
> > was
> > >> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties
> and
> > >> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the
> decks
> > >> and
> > >> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
> > >>
> > >> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
> > >> level.
> > >> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year
> later
> > >> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating
> a
> > >> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
> > >>
> > >> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal,
> > dark,
> > >> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian
> Lehman
> > >> in
> > >> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
> > >> Compound,
> > >> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from
> > many
> > >> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing,
> Dave
> > >> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more.
> Together
> > >> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
> > >> Attack
> > >> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both
> the
> > >> mind
> > >> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets
> > which
> > >> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.
>  When
> > >> not
> > >> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
> > >> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
> > >>
> > >> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper
> echelons
> > of
> > >> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The
> > Chains"
> > >> on
> > >> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on
> > his
> > >> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for
> Dubfire,
> > as
> > >> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and
> Adam
> > >> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly
> a
> > >> name
> > >> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
> > >>
> > >>
> > >> ===> LINKS:
> > >>
> > >> Dustin Zahn's website:
> > >> http://www.enemyrecords.com/
> > >>
> > >> Dustin Zahn on MySpace (with music samples):
> > >> http://www.myspace.com/dustinzahn
