Subject: Re: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Mike Shannon (Plus 8) +  Dustin Zahn live (Drumcode)

Back when I was at Live365 we had a booth a Jupiter confrence down in LA.  We decided that we would have this one guy Andy mix from CDs in our booth and broadcast it live from the show floor.  One of the speakers at the conference was Chuck D and he stopped by our booth where Andy was "mixing" (he couldn't really beat match) from a couple of 1st generation Pioneer CD DJs. Chuck made a few derogatory comments about the perversity of DJing from CDs and in particular the faux scratching effects and wandered on.  This would have been around 2000.  But I bet he's 100% digital now.

I've been buying vinyl since I was 15 and that was a fucking long time ago.  I bought a lot of my vinyl at Rather Ripped Records in Berkeley back in the day way before I was interested in dance music.  (look it up) But really I just can't justify it anymore.  There are some many tracks that you just can't find on vinyl now that are just a click away.  And OpenMind shut down finally...

Yes I'm pretty much done with the black crack.  I think.

Peter



----- Original Message ----
From: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
To: Greg Bird <bird415@gmail.com>; Ben Haus <benhaus@gmail.com>
Cc: SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Friday, February 6, 2009 1:55:05 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] w/ Mike Shannon (Plus 8) +  Dustin Zahn live (Drumcode)

With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event (that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows my mind.

To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then! 

Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.

I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing things at the wall until something sticks.

-George

>> ___________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> MIKE SHANNON
>>
>> (bio courtesy of residentadvisor.net)
>>
>> It's been 10 years since Mike Shannon started making a name for himself on
>> the international techno scene as a DJ, producer and label owner. Now,
>> having relocated to Berlin from Valencia via Montreal in 2007 he's
>> recently
>> crowned his first decade of active service with Memory Tree, his third
>> full
>> length to date, and his debut for another notable Canadian export - Richie
>> Hawtin's Plus 8 Records. Over the years, Mike has well proven that it's
>> not
>> just his music that makes him such a valuable asset to the techno
>> community,
>> it's his total dedication to the cause. Whether finding him standing
>> behind
>> a record shop counter or searching out new talent for his labels, it's
>> always been about bringing people together and investing in the future of
>> the scene.
>>
>> Mike first got the vinyl bug at the tender age of 12, buying house and
>> techno tunes at Play de Record in Toronto and by 15 his turntable skills
>> were already landing him gigs at local underground parties and clubs. From
>> then on, Mike's musical world expanded rapidly thanks in no small part to
>> Detroit's influential WJLB radio station which turned him on to U.R., Juan
>> Atkins and Kevin Saunderson - influences that still play a big role in his
>> approach to music today. To satisfy his appetite for all things Techno, he
>> was soon managing the orders at Speed Records in his hometown of
>> Kitchener,
>> Ontario where he continued his education; importing cutting edge sounds
>> from
>> across Europe.
>>
>> Throughout that time, Mike was out DJing and clubbing from Detroit to
>> Toronto, making connections and building up a solid network of producers
>> and
>> artists, which led to the inevitable formation of his own label Cynosure
>> in
>> 1999. A couple of years later, he teamed up with Jeff Milligan on the more
>> experimental Revolver Canada imprint. Both labels have since developed
>> into
>> highly respected and trusted sources, subsequently raising the profile of
>> Canada's electronic music scene by providing then unknown producers such
>> as
>> Akufen and Deadbeat an international platform to spread their distinctive
>> sound throughout the world. Beyond developing homegrown talent, both
>> imprints continue to invite an inspired selection of international artists
>> including Pier Bucci, Monolake and Brett Johnson to name a few.
>>
>> For Mike it's always been a question of choosing uncompromising artists
>> who
>> possess a unique and original voice - an attitude that also defines his
>> own
>> work whether recording as John Shananigans, The Sunaj Assassins or under
>> his
>> own name. There's a distinctive feel to his music that's both dark and
>> soulful, that stays true to his roots while embracing the future and never
>> fails to deliver a flurry of kick-ass, funk infected beats easily proven
>> by
>> a volley of timeless singles over the years and his two previous full
>> lengths. Take 2001's Slight of Hand on Force Inc - an album that cemented
>> his reputation as an up-and-coming Minimal Techno producer and 2005's
>> Possible Conclusions to Stories That Never End - a collection of
>> chilled-out
>> Electronica inspired by his musical odyssey through out Chile in 2003.
>>
>> Mike's recent move to Berlin represents the fulfillment of another chapter
>> in his musical career and with so many influential Canadian producers
>> having
>> taken up residence in the German capital over the last few years, it's a
>> chance to hook up with old friends again and start collaborating on new
>> plans and ideas, just like the old days. Then of course there's the new
>> album, the accompanying remix projects and the immediate matter of
>> fatherhood to make 2008 something of a milestone both professionally and
>> personally.
>>
>>

>> ____________________________________________________
>>
>>
>> DUSTIN ZAHN
>>
>> After being influenced by mix-tapes of artists such as Richie Hawtin,
>> Dustin
>> began writing music purely for fun. Shortly after, Dustin met
>> future-partner
>> Ian Lehman, who was established in the mid-west rave scene. Ian explained
>> to
>> him that music similar to his was played at parties called raves. Ian
>> invited him to one of his shows and Dustin took his offer to see what he
>> was
>> talking about. After being exposed to just one party, Dustin knew this was
>> his future. Dustin started doing a Live PA at various local parties and
>> quickly became a favorite. After a year, Dustin stepped up to the decks
>> and
>> won just as much respect as he did with his productions.
>>
>> In early 2001, Dustin and Ian both agreed to take things to the next
>> level.
>> They put a halt on bookings and concentrated on the studio. A year later
>> their work had emerged onto vinyl and all over the internet, creating a
>> serious buzz. Abiotic was born, and the duo formed The Attack People.
>>
>> A few words can easily describe Dustin Zahn's style: moody, tribal, dark,
>> and hypnotic. Since Dustin co-founded Abiotic Recordings with Ian Lehman
>> in
>> 2001, he's finished projects for labels such as Invasion, Mankind,
>> Compound,
>> GFR, Humanoid, and many others. His tracks have received support from many
>> of techno's top DJs, including Adam Beyer, Ben Sims, Chris Liebing, Dave
>> Clarke, Umek, Cari Lekebusch, Patrik Skoog, and countless more. Together
>> with partner Ian Lehman they perform a Live PA under the moniker "The
>> Attack
>> People," a project concentrating on moody, futuristic funk for both the
>> mind
>> and dance floor. Zahn is also known for his diverse 3-table DJ sets which
>> have brought him all over the U.S., to Europe, and South America.  When
>> not
>> in the studio or DJing around the globe, he also co-promotes some of
>> Minneapolis' biggest techno parties.
>>
>> In recent years Dustin has made a steady ascent into the upper echelons of
>> techno producers as a solo artist, with releases like "Moving The Chains"
>> on
>> Drumcode and "Analog God" on Droid Recordings, as well as many more on his
>> own label, Enemy Records.  Future releases include a remix for Dubfire, as
>> well as tracks on Paco Osuna's Mindshake, Radio Slave's Rekids, and Adam
>> Beyer's Truesoul labels.  Clearly on a roll, Dustin Zahn is certainly a
>> name
>> the techno world will be hearing much more of.
>>
>>

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] ARGs,  Raves and technology

rory's thread below about trent reznor's involvement in ARGs has given 
me an idea ...

has anybody participated in ARGs (alternative reality games)?  i've 
heard about these and the concept is really crazy. its like the closest 
thing to the movie 'the game' with sean penn and michael douglas (ok 
movie, good concept). i've heard of major corporations take part in 
stuff like this by giving keys to audi cars, jumping into speed boats 
and if the people participate in this get really heavy into it, they 
start having other participants call each other to set each other up 
meetings to create counter intelligence and CIA type games.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternate_reality_games

seems like some sort of thing that ravers might just be into.. maybe 
having ARGs to get to a party? sort of a fun map point scavenger hunt. 
or chalking to get to wifi points in the city to get info or keys for 
coded information and free music for an event, like mix cds for artists 
and such. i would love to see the journey to a party become half the fun 
of the experience or maybe even the entire experience. who knows? all i 
know is that the standard for raves, while it has always been awesome, 
hasn't changed in (god) 20 years. since technology and the people 
involved in the scene have evolved technologically as well it would be 
fun to incorporate some technology into the aspect of raves again.

maybe it is time to see some more craziness and inventive ideas, 
especially if every one has a basic computer in their pocket such as a 
cell phone or an i phone.. maybe incorporate binary code into a map 
point like graff artist invader has done (or kanye west has done to bite 
him): http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ye5YFO4Sy0E

maybe we can incorporate something into college radio? mess with you 
tube, ebay or mess with google earth... or just do something 
interesting. there's so much potential for something awesome to happen 
since so many of us are into IT and design and all sorts of technology. 
it seems like a no brainer to let this aspect creep into our party scene.

maybe instead of one party, there can be several small ones and one fee 
for all as long as the stamp and or wrist tags are valid and have good 
security they can be valid for all events. i'm sure there are little 
locations that could work out and if one is busted the many other party 
cells could survive.

i don't know.. just think of fun things and let's do it. *i'm bored*. 
let's collaborate and have a good time. i'm down to donate ideas, time, 
sound and a space if anyone wants to throw down.

respecty,
sean ocean

FAKE WRITING STYLE 101 FOR PauL-E-wOg

Do's:
1) Choose a style and stick with it.
2) Use appropriate linguistic style to the audience you are pandering too.
3) Use punctuation.
4) Sign your name. Your real name.
5) Use this lesson if you have to live in separate worlds (like work,
work-friends, hobbies, etc). It only ever works out if you are real, and
just choosing to use the appropriate lingo at the appropriate time. You
would not want to talk to your drinking buddies like you talk to your boss.


Dont's:
1) Try to use teenage slang.
2) Use vocabulary that does not fit with 1).
3) Do not leave out all punctuation in an effort to create a style. It is a
giveaway, especially if you are able to use 12th grade adjectives.
4) Make up a name that is fake. If you have to create a fake ID to join a
community, then you are either someone who is banned, there to promote your
real self, there for ill-intent, or about to hate on someone.
5) If you do 4), you are lame. If you cannot say what you want to as
yourself, then you are not a self at all.



"Wow.. I am in awe of the success of it all and how the novelty ceases to
wear off"

"Omg I was so lucky"

"and omg that was incredible"

"I can't even count how many parties I went to"

"I wish I could like take some"

--000e0cd2beb43b891904626f826b--

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] Vinyl, etc.


On Fri, 6 Feb 2009, George Cochrane wrote:
-&e->With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event 
-&e->(that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail 
-&e->on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am 
-&e->good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout 
-&e->this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you 
-&e->aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows 
-&e->my mind.

It's a choice, not a holy war.  I know how to play off cds, I know how 
Traktor works, I helped develop a product that works the way FS or Serrato 
do, and um...

Vinyl is more fun for me.  More fun to watch, more fun to select, and 
beautifully primal.  It won't last forever, I know it's dying (well, at 
least to some degree it already has), and if people want to throw an 
occasional event that pimps it PLEASE DO.  It's a neat thing!

It's like saying a fist is an inferior weapon to a gun, therefore we 
should ban boxing...

-&e->To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then! 
-&e->
-&e->Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun 
-&e->paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your 
-&e->entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard 
-&e->drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come 
-&e->out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun 
-&e->lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with 
-&e->an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads 
-&e->have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any 
-&e->of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs 
-&e->use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.

Wedding DJs existed before hip hop and we're not going to view them as a 
high point of the art, are we?  I don't think history = validity here.  
Oh, also, I *wish* my crate weighed 30pounds.  Try more like 60+ for my 
cubic foot of lameness (which I almost need to bring if I'm hotmixing).

-&e->I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- 
-&e->but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is 

You still ride a fixie?  You still cherish your tube amps, or your vintage 
bass or mic pre's or that silly synth you could easily replace with a 
plugin?  C'mon, in every "cool-guy fetishist" thing, there's something 
valid.

-&e->just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me 
-&e->about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format 
-&e->over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing 
-&e->things at the wall until something sticks.

No, it means a bunch of cranks with lots of old vinyl want to try throwing 
parties where they play the way they remember it, when it seemed DJing was 
more of an artform.  I know I fall into this camp.  Maybe it's the 
thousands I pumped into vinyl, maybe it's the fact that moving where I 
live is nearly impossible for me thanks to this collection, maybe it's 
disillusionment with the fact that it's never going to be that way 
again... I don't think there's much "cool-guy fetishism" in my defense of 
it.  It was more fun to watch, more fun to do, and helped foster a level 
of trust in the artform as almost everything was visible and right there.

It used to be, maybe 10 years ago that it was an unspeakable crime to 
find out a DJ was "playing off a DAT", but a lot of the DJs playing "sets" 
I've seen could take a bullet to the face while playing, and all that 
would change is there would be a lot less annoying filter sweeps, poorly 
timed cuts and cheerleading going on.  DJing has been wholly democratized, 
almost anyone with iTunes or WMP pours over sets of music, anyone who can 
click a space bar to the beat can beatmatch now, and despite all this 
awesome potential, DJing as an artform has taken a bit of a dive in my 
opinion.

I don't expect everyone to agree, and I don't expect every event to be 
promoted as "Vinyl Only", but let the old curmedgeons have their fun with 
their mystical black crack, their analog sound systems, their old school 
Rane mixers, while passing out cassettes of their mixes, etc.

Andy 'Now if I could just find a good old fashioned rotary cell phone' W

p.s. if you search SFR archives you can find me passionately arguing a 
point similar to yours a few years back George, but sadly time has brought 
us all the trappings of technology and it sorta ruined DJing as a 
performance medium to a degree as far as I'm concerned.  As far as fun to 
watchness goes, and being able to connect with what people are doing... 
vinyl > live pa on outboard gear > cds > anything involving a laptop.  
Seeing media change helps, seeing non-modal (same button does same thing 
all the time, like a key on a piano vs. say, a mouse click) buttons helps, 
seeing people dig through boxes or books of cds lets you know they are 
"searching"... on a laptop, they might be playing their premixed set out 
of iTunes and checking their stocks... you just don't know.

---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

> Traktor works, I helped develop a product that works the way FS or Serrato 
> do, and um...
>
> Vinyl is more fun for me.  More fun to watch, more fun to select, and 
> beautifully primal.  It won't last forever, I know it's dying (well, at 
> least to some degree it already has), and if people want to throw an 
> occasional event that pimps it PLEASE DO.  It's a neat thing!
>
> It's like saying a fist is an inferior weapon to a gun, therefore we 
> should ban boxing...
>
> -&e->To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then! 
> -&e->
> -&e->Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun 
> -&e->paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your 
> -&e->entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard 
> -&e->drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come 
> -&e->out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun 
> -&e->lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with 
> -&e->an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads 
> -&e->have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any 
> -&e->of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs 
> -&e->use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.
>
> Wedding DJs existed before hip hop and we're not going to view them as a 
> high point of the art, are we?  I don't think history = validity here.  
> Oh, also, I *wish* my crate weighed 30pounds.  Try more like 60+ for my 
> cubic foot of lameness (which I almost need to bring if I'm hotmixing).
>
> -&e->I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- 
> -&e->but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is 
>
> You still ride a fixie?  You still cherish your tube amps, or your vintage 
> bass or mic pre's or that silly synth you could easily replace with a 
> plugin?  C'mon, in every "cool-guy fetishist" thing, there's something 
> valid.
>
> -&e->just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me 
> -&e->about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format 
> -&e->over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing 
> -&e->things at the wall until something sticks.
>
> No, it means a bunch of cranks with lots of old vinyl want to try throwing 
> parties where they play the way they remember it, when it seemed DJing was 
> more of an artform.  I know I fall into this camp.  Maybe it's the 
> thousands I pumped into vinyl, maybe it's the fact that moving where I 
> live is nearly impossible for me thanks to this collection, maybe it's 
> disillusionment with the fact that it's never going to be that way 
> again... I don't think there's much "cool-guy fetishism" in my defense of 
> it.  It was more fun to watch, more fun to do, and helped foster a level 
> of trust in the artform as almost everything was visible and right there.
>
> It used to be, maybe 10 years ago that it was an unspeakable crime to 
> find out a DJ was "playing off a DAT", but a lot of the DJs playing "sets" 
> I've seen could take a bullet to the face while playing, and all that 
> would change is there would be a lot less annoying filter sweeps, poorly 
> timed cuts and cheerleading going on.  DJing has been wholly democratized, 
> almost anyone with iTunes or WMP pours over sets of music, anyone who can 
> click a space bar to the beat can beatmatch now, and despite all this 
> awesome potential, DJing as an artform has taken a bit of a dive in my 
> opinion.
>
> I don't expect everyone to agree, and I don't expect every event to be 
> promoted as "Vinyl Only", but let the old curmedgeons have their fun with

> Rane mixers, while passing out cassettes of their mixes, etc.

> watchness goes, and being able to connect with what people are doing... 
> vinyl > live pa on outboard gear > cds > anything involving a laptop.  
> Seeing media change helps, seeing non-modal (same button does same thing 
> all the time, like a key on a piano vs. say, a mouse click) buttons helps,

----- Original Message ----
From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
To: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
Cc: SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Monday, February 9, 2009 9:51:31 AM
Subject: [sfraves] Vinyl, etc.


On Fri, 6 Feb 2009, George Cochrane wrote:
-&e->With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event 
-&e->(that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail 
-&e->on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am 
-&e->good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout 
-&e->this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you 
-&e->aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows 
-&e->my mind.

It's a choice, not a holy war.  I know how to play off cds, I know how 
Traktor works, I helped develop a product that works the way FS or Serrato 
do, and um...

Vinyl is more fun for me.  More fun to watch, more fun to select, and 
beautifully primal.  It won't last forever, I know it's dying (well, at 
least to some degree it already has), and if people want to throw an 
occasional event that pimps it PLEASE DO.  It's a neat thing!

It's like saying a fist is an inferior weapon to a gun, therefore we 
should ban boxing...

-&e->To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then! 
-&e->
-&e->Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun 
-&e->paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your 
-&e->entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard 
-&e->drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come 
-&e->out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun 
-&e->lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with 
-&e->an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads 
-&e->have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any 
-&e->of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those djs 
-&e->use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.

Wedding DJs existed before hip hop and we're not going to view them as a 
high point of the art, are we?  I don't think history = validity here.  
Oh, also, I *wish* my crate weighed 30pounds.  Try more like 60+ for my 
cubic foot of lameness (which I almost need to bring if I'm hotmixing).

-&e->I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms, too- 
-&e->but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is 

You still ride a fixie?  You still cherish your tube amps, or your vintage 
bass or mic pre's or that silly synth you could easily replace with a 
plugin?  C'mon, in every "cool-guy fetishist" thing, there's something 
valid.

-&e->just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me 
-&e->about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format 
-&e->over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep throwing 
-&e->things at the wall until something sticks.

No, it means a bunch of cranks with lots of old vinyl want to try throwing 
parties where they play the way they remember it, when it seemed DJing was 
more of an artform.  I know I fall into this camp.  Maybe it's the 
thousands I pumped into vinyl, maybe it's the fact that moving where I 
live is nearly impossible for me thanks to this collection, maybe it's 
disillusionment with the fact that it's never going to be that way 
again... I don't think there's much "cool-guy fetishism" in my defense of 
it.  It was more fun to watch, more fun to do, and helped foster a level 
of trust in the artform as almost everything was visible and right there.

It used to be, maybe 10 years ago that it was an unspeakable crime to 
find out a DJ was "playing off a DAT", but a lot of the DJs playing "sets" 
I've seen could take a bullet to the face while playing, and all that 
would change is there would be a lot less annoying filter sweeps, poorly 
timed cuts and cheerleading going on.  DJing has been wholly democratized, 
almost anyone with iTunes or WMP pours over sets of music, anyone who can 
click a space bar to the beat can beatmatch now, and despite all this 
awesome potential, DJing as an artform has taken a bit of a dive in my 
opinion.

I don't expect everyone to agree, and I don't expect every event to be 
promoted as "Vinyl Only", but let the old curmedgeons have their fun with 
their mystical black crack, their analog sound systems, their old school 
Rane mixers, while passing out cassettes of their mixes, etc.

Andy 'Now if I could just find a good old fashioned rotary cell phone' W

p.s. if you search SFR archives you can find me passionately arguing a 
point similar to yours a few years back George, but sadly time has brought 
us all the trappings of technology and it sorta ruined DJing as a 
performance medium to a degree as far as I'm concerned.  As far as fun to 
watchness goes, and being able to connect with what people are doing... 
vinyl > live pa on outboard gear > cds > anything involving a laptop.  
Seeing media change helps, seeing non-modal (same button does same thing 
all the time, like a key on a piano vs. say, a mouse click) buttons helps, 
seeing people dig through boxes or books of cds lets you know they are 
"searching"... on a laptop, they might be playing their premixed set out 
of iTunes and checking their stocks... you just don't know.

> It was just 'Jason' if you met some skater kid in a
> parking lot in the
> foothills in 1985.
>
> 'Faceman' was tbe mod-punk that came from
> Sacramento in the years
> thereafter
>
> 'Private Borenstein' was the meta-rebellious
> intellectual serving our
> country in Ansbach 1993.
>
> It was 'Stillwind' if you met an enlightened soul
> in San Francisco in
> '98...
> or maybe 'DJ Stillwind' if you knew him by his
> funky shade of trance.
>
> Steeween-San was tbe crazy American that chased the sunset
> west in search
> of a pretty girl, a dream job, and the world's finest
> Sashimi...
>
> DJ Michael Alamode was the arcade avatar that Japanese
> gamers came to know
> and love.
>
> To me he was always just "bro".
>
> He was my best friend.
>
> Stillwind died by the hand of nature on Sunday February
> 8th, 2009.
>
> In the Fall of 2008 - a few months after Mr . Wind took
> Bill and I on an
> epic snowboarding trip to Hokkaido - he miraculously
> survived an abdominal
> aneurysm. He thereafter learned of further arterial
> weaknesses and what was
> likely a genetic predisposition. Stillwind's girlfriend
> and his mom showed
> incredible care and compassion in his recovery from that
> surgery. He told
> me in December that he would accept the risk of sudden
> death - interrupting
> a life fully lived, rather than undergo a surgery that
> would have likely
> left him incapable of such. The last time we spoke, he
> seemed to be living
> that life as he wished.
>

Paul Simcovich-Hayden wrote:
>

> On Mon, Feb 9, 2009 at 3:20 PM, STML <dj.stml@gmail.com> wrote:
>
>> I'm sort of over the whole vinyl vs. puter argument at this stage. Each
>> has it's merits. Personally, most of the new music I like isn't coming out
>> on vinyl, so it's a moot point. Having said that, theres a lot to be said
>> for Andy's points. There's also a lot to be said for the scores of excellent
>> tunes I just couldn't be assed to digitize. It's a lot of fun to bang out a
>> set of gloriously self indulgent vinyl monsters occasionally.
>>
>>
>> On Mon, Feb 9, 2009 at 11:57 AM, George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com
>> > wrote:
>>
>>> Good points, monsieur.
>>>
>>> Bingbong!
>>>
>>>
>>>
>>> ----- Original Message ----
>>> From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
>>> To: George Cochrane <newstylesound@yahoo.com>
>>> Cc: SFRaves <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>>> Sent: Monday, February 9, 2009 9:51:31 AM
>>> Subject: [sfraves] Vinyl, etc.
>>>
>>>
>>> On Fri, 6 Feb 2009, George Cochrane wrote:
>>> -&e->With respect to the nice folks putting on that "All Vinyl" event
>>> -&e->(that I will probably be at): Can I just take a sec to politely rail
>>> -&e->on this vinyl elitist thing that's happening at the moment?  I am
>>> -&e->good friends with a BUNCH of talented DJs that have started to spout
>>> -&e->this "Vinyl only, duh bra if you're not playing records then you
>>> -&e->aren't really DJing..." line in the last year or so.  Totally blows
>>> -&e->my mind.
>>>
>>> It's a choice, not a holy war.  I know how to play off cds, I know how
>>> Traktor works, I helped develop a product that works the way FS or
>>> Serrato
>>> do, and um...
>>>
>>> Vinyl is more fun for me.  More fun to watch, more fun to select, and
>>> beautifully primal.  It won't last forever, I know it's dying (well, at
>>> least to some degree it already has), and if people want to throw an
>>> occasional event that pimps it PLEASE DO.  It's a neat thing!
>>>
>>> It's like saying a fist is an inferior weapon to a gun, therefore we
>>> should ban boxing...
>>>
>>> -&e->To these folks, I kinda have to say, fine then!
>>> -&e->
>>> -&e->Say goodbye to playing unreleased music (yours or others), have fun
>>> -&e->paying $9-12 bucks for a single decent track, have fun with your
>>> -&e->entire bedroom of records that would fit on a rather modest hard
>>> -&e->drive, enjoy not having access to most of the cool tech that's come
>>> -&e->out for djing in the last 10 years...  ...and most of all, have fun
>>> -&e->lugging your 30lb crate to every gig while I show up on my bike with
>>> -&e->an 8lb backpack and 10x as much music.  All I know is, hip-hop heads
>>> -&e->have been vinyl-loving, crate-digging record purists longer than any
>>> -&e->of us electronic music people can lay claim to, and ~90% of those
>>> djs
>>> -&e->use Scratch at this point.  Case kinda closed.
>>>
>>> Wedding DJs existed before hip hop and we're not going to view them as a
>>> high point of the art, are we?  I don't think history = validity here.
>>> Oh, also, I *wish* my crate weighed 30pounds.  Try more like 60+ for my
>>> cubic foot of lameness (which I almost need to bring if I'm hotmixing).
>>>
>>> -&e->I'm all for people celebrating vinyl, I think it has its charms,
>>> too-
>>> -&e->but to try to turn it into some kind of cool-guy fetishism thing is
>>>
>>> You still ride a fixie?  You still cherish your tube amps, or your
>>> vintage
>>> bass or mic pre's or that silly synth you could easily replace with a
>>> plugin?  C'mon, in every "cool-guy fetishist" thing, there's something
>>> valid.
>>>
>>> -&e->just retarded.  The only thing an "all vinyl" designation tells me
>>> -&e->about a party is that the people I'm about to see have chosen format
>>> -&e->over function.  I guess that's marketing for you- gotta keep
>>> throwing
>>> -&e->things at the wall until something sticks.
>>>
>>> No, it means a bunch of cranks with lots of old vinyl want to try
>>> throwing
>>> parties where they play the way they remember it, when it seemed DJing
>>> was
>>> more of an artform.  I know I fall into this camp.  Maybe it's the
>>> thousands I pumped into vinyl, maybe it's the fact that moving where I
>>> live is nearly impossible for me thanks to this collection, maybe it's
>>> disillusionment with the fact that it's never going to be that way
>>> again... I don't think there's much "cool-guy fetishism" in my defense of
>>> it.  It was more fun to watch, more fun to do, and helped foster a level
>>> of trust in the artform as almost everything was visible and right there.
>>>
>>> It used to be, maybe 10 years ago that it was an unspeakable crime to
>>> find out a DJ was "playing off a DAT", but a lot of the DJs playing
>>> "sets"
>>> I've seen could take a bullet to the face while playing, and all that
>>> would change is there would be a lot less annoying filter sweeps, poorly
>>> timed cuts and cheerleading going on.  DJing has been wholly
>>> democratized,
>>> almost anyone with iTunes or WMP pours over sets of music, anyone who can
>>> click a space bar to the beat can beatmatch now, and despite all this
>>> awesome potential, DJing as an artform has taken a bit of a dive in my
>>> opinion.
>>>
>>> I don't expect everyone to agree, and I don't expect every event to be
>>> promoted as "Vinyl Only", but let the old curmedgeons have their fun with
>>> their mystical black crack, their analog sound systems, their old school
>>> Rane mixers, while passing out cassettes of their mixes, etc.
>>>
>>> Andy 'Now if I could just find a good old fashioned rotary cell phone' W
>>>
>>> p.s. if you search SFR archives you can find me passionately arguing a
>>> point similar to yours a few years back George, but sadly time has
>>> brought
>>> us all the trappings of technology and it sorta ruined DJing as a
>>> performance medium to a degree as far as I'm concerned.  As far as fun to
>>> watchness goes, and being able to connect with what people are doing...
>>> vinyl > live pa on outboard gear > cds > anything involving a laptop.
>>> Seeing media change helps, seeing non-modal (same button does same thing
>>> all the time, like a key on a piano vs. say, a mouse click) buttons
>>> helps,
>>> seeing people dig through boxes or books of cds lets you know they are
>>> "searching"... on a laptop, they might be playing their premixed set out
>>> of iTunes and checking their stocks... you just don't know.
>>>

To my crotchety old raver friends...

My debut release, Free Spirit Lost Soul EP, on SubSensory Recordings, is out
on Beatport today!

The title track is a deep, syncopated, slow burning techno track for
afterhours dancefloors. Portland's DJ Jak and Lil' Roj provided the remix, a
funky tech-house treatment. The EP also features Jak's driving, melodic
techno track Harmonix, along with my deep tech-house remix.

C.Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul EP - Beatport
Link<https://www.beatport.com/en-US/html/content/release/detail/156470/free_spirit_lost_soul_ep>

1. C. Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul (Original Mix)
2. C. Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul (JAK & Lil' Roj Remix)
3. Jack Coleman - Harmonix
4. Jack Coleman - Harmonix (C. Faith's Sunrise Mix)

You can also hear two of the tracks in full on my Soundcloud page --->
www.soundcloud.com/cfaith


Love Chelsea
www.myspace.com/chelcfaithmusic
www.soundcloud.com/cfaith

Subject: Re: [sfraves] ARGs,  Raves and technology

well i've seen the rule being broken a few times and as far as i know 
the fnf chat list is more about bacon and politics than much anything 
else. i thought the post was way more rave related but the post 
originated on fnf. but i debated about this quandry.. when the better 
conversations with the trueskool heads ignore SFR when something 
interesting comes up that could change the way we think about raves.. 
shouldn't way more people know about it? anyway.. if nobody is going to 
do anything about ARGs and raves i'm going to give it a shot just to be 
mischievous. cheap mystery thumb drives, ebay trickery, craigslist 
posts, you tube and media hacks. it seems like it could be alot of fun.  
for starters, i could just drop stuff into my network folder and see who 
downloads it based on who's logged into the LAN. or if someone is over 
for an integrated broadcast they can get some goodies just for showing 
up like past sets etc. fun fun.

sean.

> On Sat, 7 Feb 2009, sean ocean wrote:

> -&e->rory's thread below about trent reznor's involvement in ARGs has given me
> -&e->an idea ...
> -&e->
> -&e->has anybody participated in ARGs (alternative reality games)?  i've heard
> -&e->about these and the concept is really crazy. its like the closest thing to
> -&e->the movie 'the game' with sean penn and michael douglas (ok movie, good
> -&e->concept). i've heard of major corporations take part in stuff like this by
> -&e->giving keys to audi cars, jumping into speed boats and if the people
> -&e->participate in this get really heavy into it, they start having other
> -&e->participants call each other to set each other up meetings to create
> -&e->counter intelligence and CIA type games.
> -&e->
> -&e->http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternate_reality_games
> -&e->
> -&e->seems like some sort of thing that ravers might just be into.. maybe having
> -&e->ARGs to get to a party? sort of a fun map point scavenger hunt. or chalking
> -&e->to get to wifi points in the city to get info or keys for coded information
> -&e->and free music for an event, like mix cds for artists and such. i would
> -&e->love to see the journey to a party become half the fun of the experience or
> -&e->maybe even the entire experience. who knows? all i know is that the
> -&e->standard for raves, while it has always been awesome, hasn't changed in
> -&e->(god) 20 years. since technology and the people involved in the scene have
> -&e->evolved technologically as well it would be fun to incorporate some
> -&e->technology into the aspect of raves again.
> -&e->
> -&e->maybe it is time to see some more craziness and inventive ideas, especially
> -&e->if every one has a basic computer in their pocket such as a cell phone or
> -&e->an i phone.. maybe incorporate binary code into a map point like graff
> -&e->artist invader has done (or kanye west has done to bite him):
> -&e->http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ye5YFO4Sy0E
> -&e->
> -&e->maybe we can incorporate something into college radio? mess with you tube,
> -&e->ebay or mess with google earth... or just do something interesting. there's
> -&e->so much potential for something awesome to happen since so many of us are
> -&e->into IT and design and all sorts of technology. it seems like a no brainer
> -&e->to let this aspect creep into our party scene.
> -&e->
> -&e->maybe instead of one party, there can be several small ones and one fee for
> -&e->all as long as the stamp and or wrist tags are valid and have good security
> -&e->they can be valid for all events. i'm sure there are little locations that
> -&e->could work out and if one is busted the many other party cells could
> -&e->survive.
> -&e->
> -&e->i don't know.. just think of fun things and let's do it. *i'm bored*. let's
> -&e->collaborate and have a good time. i'm down to donate ideas, time, sound and
> -&e->a space if anyone wants to throw down.

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] [bsp] AFTERGLOW - an evening of mellow electronics - Sunday @ 
	Nickie's

AFTERGLOW was conceived as a chance to wind down after a long weekend
by listening to some chill music and having a few drinks with friends.  The
idea is to allow some of SF's talented and multi-faceted dance music
DJ's an opportunity to dig deeper into their collections and play music they
wouldn't be able to in a club setting. Anything's game, from ambient to dub
techno, trip-hop, idm, atmospheric drum n bass, downtempo, future jazz,
deep house and beyond.

_______________________________________________________________


Our second event takes place this Sunday, February 15th and features
the relaxing and heady musical stylings of Ambient Mafia members:


SHANE  (FnF, Cloud Factory, Ambient Mafia)

and

HARKEN  (Urban Wasteland, FnF, Ambient Mafia)


plus residents:  Congruence, Mike Perry, & Greg Bird


Afterglow website:  (check out the flyer here)
http://www.afterglowsf.com

Afterglow on MySpace:  (add us!)
http://www.myspace.com/afterglowsf

________________________________________________________________


Located @ the all new:

-----[ NICKIE'S ]-----

466 Haight Street, SF
10pm - 1am / FREE

full bar / kitchen open til 1am
http://www.nickies.com

_______________________________________________________________


More about this month's guests:


Shane     (FnF, Cloud Factory, Ambient Mafia)

After NASA brought Shane to the Bay Area in 1997, he eventually
decided to go to a warehouse party to see what the hell everyone was
raving about. Three months later he'd bought turntables, a ton of
vinyl, and soon became a core member of several Bay Area collectives
including Epiphany, Viberation and Friends and Family. An innaugural
member of the Ambient Mafia, Shane looks forward many things, such as
blowing minds -- one banana at a time. He also likes mimosas, walks in
the park, robotic death, driving fast and bacon.


Harken     (Urban Wasteland, FnF, Ambient Mafia)

Harken started spinning records in 1997 upon hearing LTJ Bukem's
seminal Logical Progression. After several underground appearances
with the likes of Epiphany, Plate Tectonics, and High Jinx, he was
approached by Redstickman, and asked to be a founding member of the
Ambient Mafia. Little did he know that the key word there was
"member".

______________________________________________________________


It's gonna be a big weekend, and I'm sure by Sunday we'll be ready to trade
in the dancing shoes for some good conversation, a pint of beer and a big
ol' plate of mac n' cheese.

Let's get mellow. :)


----> Greg Bird, Mike Perry, and Matt Wilder

---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

From: Chelsea Faith <chelcfaith@gmail.com>

Subject: [sfraves] BSP - C. Faith's 'Free Spirit Lost Soul' out on Beatport today <3

To my crotchety old raver friends...

My debut release, Free Spirit Lost Soul EP, on SubSensory Recordings, is out
on Beatport today!

The title track is a deep, syncopated, slow burning techno track for
afterhours dancefloors. Portland's DJ Jak and Lil' Roj provided the remix, a
funky tech-house treatment. The EP also features Jak's driving, melodic
techno track Harmonix, along with my deep tech-house remix.

C.Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul EP - Beatport
Link<https://www.beatport.com/en-US/html/content/release/detail/156470/free_spirit_lost_soul_ep>

1. C. Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul (Original Mix)
2. C. Faith - Free Spirit Lost Soul (JAK & Lil' Roj Remix)
3. Jack Coleman - Harmonix
4. Jack Coleman - Harmonix (C. Faith's Sunrise Mix)

You can also hear two of the tracks in full on my Soundcloud page --->
www.soundcloud.com/cfaith


Love Chelsea
www.myspace.com/chelcfaithmusic
www.soundcloud.com/cfaith

Another petition campaign.


---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Fri, 13 Feb 2009 13:48:43 -0500
From: "Cleve Jones, for Courage Campaign" <info@couragecampaign.org>
Subject: President Clinton: What would Harvey Milk do?

Dear Courage Campaign supporter,

President Bill Clinton will be making a big mistake on Sunday. Unless we 
act now to stop him. Let me tell you why.

If you've seen the film "MILK", you may know that I worked with Harvey 
Milk in the 1970s, including on a campaign to boycott Coors Beer for the 
company's anti-gay hiring policies and belligerent stance in contract 
negotiations towards their workers.

The Coors Beer Boycott taught me an unforgettable lesson about the power 
of coalitions in the struggle for equality. That lesson is being 
replicated today in the successful Manchester Hyatt Boycott in San 
Diego.

To the the surprise of many, President Clinton is scheduled to give a 
paid speech this Sunday at the Manchester Hyatt to the annual convention 
of the International Franchise Association. To give this speech, 
President Clinton will have to violate a union boycott and labor dispute 
-- the workers at the hotel lack job security and the housekeepers face 
onerous workloads.

But that's not all. President Clinton will also be offending supporters 
of marriage equality, including myself. Doug Manchester, the owner of 
the hotel, contributed $125,000 in early seed money to the Proposition 8 
campaign.

We can't let this happen. President Clinton has the power to move his 
speech away from the Manchester Hyatt. And you have the power to 
convince him before it's too late. Please sign the Courage Campaign's 
petition to President Clinton immediately and we will do everything in 
our power to get your signatures to him ASAP:

http://www.couragecampaign.org/Clinton

It is ironic that, by showing up at the Manchester Hyatt on Sunday, 
President Clinton will provide comfort to Ken Starr and the Prop 8 Legal 
Defense Fund, who are now trying to defend the constitutionality of Prop 
8 before the state Supreme Court. Doug Manchester's significant $125,000 
contribution to the "Yes on 8" campaign helped pass Prop 8 -- money that 
made Starr's case possible.

I think President Clinton should move his speech to another hotel in the 
area that treats its workers -- and the LGBT community -- with respect. 
If he doesn't, he will see me, and likely many others, this Sunday on 
the sidewalk in front of the Manchester Hyatt.

That is exactly where Harvey Milk would want me -- and you -- to be. 
While you may not be able join us there, I hope you'll add your 
signature right now and let President Clinton know what you think before 
Sunday:

http://www.couragecampaign.org/Clinton

Thank you for helping the Courage Campaign and UNITE HERE build a 
broad-based coalition for equal rights and economic justice in 
California and across the country.

Cleve Jones
UNITE HERE

..............

The Courage Campaign is an online organizing network that empowers over 
500,000 grassroots and netroots activists to push for progressive change 
in California.

To power our campaign to repeal Prop 8, please chip in what you can 
today:

http://www.couragecampaign.org/PowerTheRepeal


----
Paid for by Courage Campaign.

--- On Fri, 2/13/09, J.C. <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu> wrote:

> From: J.C. <dougm@kzsu.stanford.edu>
> Subject: [sfraves] NRR: President Clinton: What would Harvey Milk do?
> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> Date: Friday, February 13, 2009, 10:55 AM
> Another petition campaign.
> 
> 
> ---------- Forwarded message ----------
> Date: Fri, 13 Feb 2009 13:48:43 -0500
> From: "Cleve Jones, for Courage Campaign"
> <info@couragecampaign.org>
> Subject: President Clinton: What would Harvey Milk do?
> 
> Dear Courage Campaign supporter,
> 
> President Bill Clinton will be making a big mistake on
> Sunday. Unless we act now to stop him. Let me tell you why.
> 
> If you've seen the film "MILK", you may know
> that I worked with Harvey Milk in the 1970s, including on a
> campaign to boycott Coors Beer for the company's
> anti-gay hiring policies and belligerent stance in contract
> negotiations towards their workers.
> 
> The Coors Beer Boycott taught me an unforgettable lesson
> about the power of coalitions in the struggle for equality.
> That lesson is being replicated today in the successful
> Manchester Hyatt Boycott in San Diego.
> 
> To the the surprise of many, President Clinton is scheduled
> to give a paid speech this Sunday at the Manchester Hyatt to
> the annual convention of the International Franchise
> Association. To give this speech, President Clinton will
> have to violate a union boycott and labor dispute -- the
> workers at the hotel lack job security and the housekeepers
> face onerous workloads.
> 
> But that's not all. President Clinton will also be
> offending supporters of marriage equality, including myself.
> Doug Manchester, the owner of the hotel, contributed
> $125,000 in early seed money to the Proposition 8 campaign.
> 
> We can't let this happen. President Clinton has the
> power to move his speech away from the Manchester Hyatt. And
> you have the power to convince him before it's too late.
> Please sign the Courage Campaign's petition to President
> Clinton immediately and we will do everything in our power
> to get your signatures to him ASAP:
> 
> http://www.couragecampaign.org/Clinton
> 
> It is ironic that, by showing up at the Manchester Hyatt on
> Sunday, President Clinton will provide comfort to Ken Starr
> and the Prop 8 Legal Defense Fund, who are now trying to
> defend the constitutionality of Prop 8 before the state
> Supreme Court. Doug Manchester's significant $125,000
> contribution to the "Yes on 8" campaign helped
> pass Prop 8 -- money that made Starr's case possible.
> 
> I think President Clinton should move his speech to another
> hotel in the area that treats its workers -- and the LGBT
> community -- with respect. If he doesn't, he will see
> me, and likely many others, this Sunday on the sidewalk in
> front of the Manchester Hyatt.
> 
> That is exactly where Harvey Milk would want me -- and you
> -- to be. While you may not be able join us there, I hope
> you'll add your signature right now and let President
> Clinton know what you think before Sunday:
> 
> http://www.couragecampaign.org/Clinton
> 
> Thank you for helping the Courage Campaign and UNITE HERE
> build a broad-based coalition for equal rights and economic
> justice in California and across the country.
> 
> Cleve Jones
> UNITE HERE
> 
> ..............
> 
> The Courage Campaign is an online organizing network that
> empowers over 500,000 grassroots and netroots activists to
> push for progressive change in California.
> 
> To power our campaign to repeal Prop 8, please chip in what
> you can today:
> 
> http://www.couragecampaign.org/PowerTheRepeal
> 
> 
> ----
> Paid for by Courage Campaign.
> 
> 
> 
> 
> ---------------------------------------------------------------------
> To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
> For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: President Clinton: What would Harvey Milk do?


The boycott Milk spearheaded and this are two totally different things.

That was a clear case of broad based discrimination in a free system.  We 
have a choice of what brand of beer to buy, or whether to buy it at all.  
Asking an individual to boycott something they're already contractually 
bound to follow through with (with the International Franchise Foundation, 
not the hotel or it's owner) is not likely something that will go through 
and we should focus on issues where the benefits merit the efforts.  If 
the union is actually on strike, his attendance could be used to raise 
awareness if effectively covered (yes, he'd cross picket lines, but it 
might force a statement which is golden free press).

Asking Clinton to take the money and donate it to the union and the repeal 
of prop8 seems to make a lot more sense.  Everybody gets to save face and 
the statement is that much stronger.

Good intentions, bad idea in my opinion.
andyw

> being replicated today in the successful Manchester Hyatt Boycott in  
> San Diego.

> the owner of the hotel, contributed $125,000 in early seed money to  
> the Proposition 8 campaign.

> That is exactly where Harvey Milk would want me -- and you -- to be.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Blessed (my new DJ mix)

Hi everyone,

I've been DJing for 13 years now, and this is the 13th mix I've made
available via tape, CD or download over my career. That puts me at a rate of
one per year, which means it's not very often I actually pull through and
finish one of these things. ;) I've never put out a mix loaded up with brand
new or upcoming music, instead it's usually a combination of old, new, and a
whole lot in between. I try to make each mix distinctly different, following
a sound, concept, or idea that forms in my head over an extended period of
playing gigs. This mix came out of my experiences playing for Ryan and
Dennis at their Life SF parties here in San Francisco. Like the Life events,
this is a full on party time house music mix, with a lot of vocals, a little
bit of gloss, and a heavy dose of funk and soul:

http://www.djandrewphelan.com/music/Andrew_Phelan_Blessed.mp3

Also, here's a link to all of my old mixes:

http://www.djandrewphelan.com/mixes.php

And the tracklist for Blessed:

1. Candy Apple feat. Anjou - Step 2 Me (Inland Knights Remix) - Shake And
Pop
2. D-t3ch - Meerkat Music - Spatula City
3. Doug Willis - Doug Dastardly (Bonus Beats) - Z Records
4. Spenitch - I'm Blessed (Maurice Fulton Original Stomp Dub) - Basement
Boys
5. Ministry of Funk - Funky Nation - Muzik X Press
6. Mario Fabriani - Good God Almighty - Fetish Recordings
7. Giom - Be Free - Amenti Music
8. The Midnight Circus - Back To The Summer (Joey Youngman Remix) - Damaged
Goods
9. Eric Davenport & Twenty Twelve - Long Time Now - Jamayka Recordings
10. Inland Knights - Lay On Me (Larrys Mango Mix) - Drop Music
11. Christian Malloni - Keep It Hot - Candy Music
12. Alexander East - Believe En Me (Lawnchair Generals Believe in West Mix -
Nordix Trax
13. Christian Malloni - You Rock - Candy Music
14. Christian Malloni - Blue Dreams - Agave
15. Larry Fives - Freezer - Drop Music

Thanks, hope you enjoy!

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: 2.20.9 DEF's Radio Integrated 'Oblique Strategies Night' Feat.
 ANDY W!

--------------000704090807090105050003
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

oblique strat flyer

What
/"Oblique Strategies Night" on DEFsf.com's Radio Integrated/
When
/Friday February 20th, 2009
9pm-? PST/
*Where*
/Bliss Factory Studios & online: http://radio.defsf.com:1200// /
*Who*
/Andy W/
*How*
/Extended DJ Set, Interview and Internet radio broadcast/

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
Yes, dear friends, it is that time once again where we shout out out to 
the world what SF techno is made of. Time to view that SF Techno is more 
about fun, good choons, good times and building slightly intoxicated 
meaningful social interactions than scene politics and aggressive social 
climbing. So this time, we are back with another installment of the ever 
fun BYOB night, Radio Integrated! This time, we are featuring one of the 
most real DJs out there that has been synonymous with SF Techno for over 
a decade, Andy W.


Andy W has been there and back from helping to throw small weeklies in 
SF Techno's darkest hours to rocking massive sound systems and 
destroying minds at its peaks with his unusual creative flair. Widely 
regarded as one of the most inspiring technical DJs to have ever come 
out of the SF scene, Andy balances heady techno with mind twisting 
tracks that make you go WTF?! While Andy may feed you weird things, he's 
still giving you something to groove on to compliment the bizarre, 
making the mix take on whole new dimensions and meaning while still 
infusing each new mix with creativity and originality. Andy W has always 
been one of the most fluid and surprising DJs to me, often putting 
himself into any situation and making it work with clarity. So it is 
with no surprise that when I came asking him to do a mix for Integrated, 
we both agreed that an extended set featuring Andy W would only be a 
proper showcase for him to flex his muscles as a DJ. This Friday's set 
should be a genre busting, quick mixing, long mixing, techno, electro, 
mind funking example of what Andy W is really about. So strap yourself 
in, this could get interesting.
+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

9-9:30 interview
9:30-? Andy W does his Laurent Garnier DJ impression

tune in:

http://radio.defsf.com:1200/
from 9pm - ? PST
http://www.defsf.com/radiointegrated/integrated

as always, if you would like to come out to chill out in person during a 
broadcast, be prepared to bring enough BYOB and snax to share, and 
please e-mail back for directions to the event, we'll leave the bass 
bins on for you. `;)

More random info and secret broadcasts:

subscribe:
radio-integrated-subsctibe@defsf.com
def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com

Sean Ocean DEF.

-- 
++++DEFsf.com "a west coast techno alliance"++++

Visit: http://www.defsf.com
west coast techno articles, news, links, music & events

++++techno news & info: def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com
++++DEF radio info: radio-integrated-subsctibe@defsf.com

--- On Wed, 2/18/09, sean ocean <seanocean@defsf.com> wrote:
From: sean ocean <seanocean@defsf.com>
Subject: [sfraves] BSP: 2.20.9 DEF's Radio Integrated 'Oblique Strategies Night' Feat. ANDY W!
To: "SFR" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Date: Wednesday, February 18, 2009, 6:38 PM




  
  




What

"Oblique Strategies Night" on DEFsf.com's Radio Integrated

When

Friday February 20th, 2009


9pm-? PST

Where

Bliss Factory Studios & online: http://radio.defsf.com:1200//


Who

Andy W

How

Extended DJ Set, Interview and Internet radio
broadcast



+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++


Yes, dear friends, it is that time once again where we shout out out to
the world what SF techno is made of. Time to view that SF Techno is
more about fun, good choons, good times and building slightly
intoxicated meaningful social interactions than scene politics and
aggressive social climbing. So this time, we are back with another
installment of the ever fun BYOB night, Radio Integrated! This time, we
are featuring one of the most real DJs out there that has been
synonymous with SF Techno for over a decade, Andy W.






Andy W has been there and back from helping to throw small weeklies in
SF Techno's darkest hours to rocking massive sound systems and
destroying minds at its peaks with his unusual creative flair. Widely
regarded as one of the most inspiring technical DJs to have ever come
out of the SF scene, Andy balances heady techno with mind twisting
tracks that make you go WTF?! While Andy may feed you weird things,
he's still giving you something to groove on to compliment the bizarre,
making the mix take on whole new dimensions and meaning while still
infusing each new mix with creativity and originality. Andy W has
always been one of the most fluid and surprising DJs to me, often
putting himself into any situation and making it work with clarity. So
it is with no surprise that when I came asking him to do a mix for
Integrated, we both agreed that an extended set featuring Andy W would
only be a proper showcase for him to flex his muscles as a DJ. This
Friday's set should be a genre busting, quick mixing, long mixing,
techno, electro, mind funking example of what Andy W is really about.
So strap yourself in, this could get interesting.


+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++




9-9:30 interview


9:30-? Andy W does his Laurent Garnier DJ impression




tune in:




http://radio.defsf.com:1200/


from 9pm - ? PST


http://www.defsf.com/radiointegrated/integrated




as always, if you would like to come out to chill out in person during
a broadcast, be prepared to bring enough BYOB and snax to share, and
please e-mail back for directions to the event, we'll leave the bass
bins on for you. `;)




More random info and secret broadcasts:




subscribe:


radio-integrated-subsctibe@defsf.com


def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com




Sean Ocean DEF.



-- 
++++DEFsf.com "a west coast techno alliance"++++

Visit: http://www.defsf.com
west coast techno articles, news, links, music & events

++++techno news & info: def-announce-subscribe@defsf.com
++++DEF radio info: radio-integrated-subsctibe@defsf.com

Yes, dear friends, it is that time once again where we shout out out to
the world what SF techno is made of. Time to view that SF Techno is
more about fun, good choons, good times and building slightly
intoxicated meaningful social interactions than scene politics and
aggressive social climbing. So this time, we are back with another
installment of the ever fun BYOB night, Radio Integrated! This time, we
are featuring one of the most real DJs out there that has been
synonymous with SF Techno for over a decade, Andy W.
<br>
<br>
<br>
Andy W has been there and back from helping to throw small weeklies in
SF Techno's darkest hours to rocking massive sound systems and
destroying minds at its peaks with his unusual creative flair. Widely
regarded as one of the most inspiring technical DJs to have ever come
out of the SF scene, Andy balances heady techno with mind twisting
tracks that make you go WTF?! While Andy may feed you weird things,
he's still giving you something to groove on to compliment the bizarre,
making the mix take on whole new dimensions and meaning while still
infusing each new mix with creativity and originality. Andy W has
always been one of the most fluid and surprising DJs to me, often
putting himself into any situation and making it work with clarity. So
it is with no surprise that when I came asking him to do a mix for
Integrated, we both agreed that an extended set featuring Andy W would
only be a proper showcase for him to flex his muscles as a DJ. This
Friday's set should be a genre busting, quick mixing, long mixing,
techno, electro, mind funking example of what Andy W is really about.
So strap yourself in, this could get interesting.

On Mon, Feb 23, 2009 at 9:30 AM, Holt Sorenson <hso@hsomusic.com> wrote:
> Please tune in to KZSU by listening to 90.1 in the Bay Area or
> pointing your web browser to http://kzsulive.stanford.edu.
>
> If you're interested in guest appearing on any of our shows
> or having a mix featured contact us using our email addresses
> or: electronicadjs@kzsu.stanford.edu
>
> Big Love Show with Jack - Mon 3PM-6PM Pacific/US
> ------------------------------------------------
>
> This week Jack is hosting somebody, cuz he always does!
>
> I didn't get a hold of him in time (doh!) so I'll
> send an update later today. But tune in, cuz it's
> always great!!!
>
> You can find out more about Jack and his show at:
> http://www.thebigloveshow.com/
>
> Eclektronik Groove w/ Holt Sorenson - Mon 9AM-12PM Pacific/US
> --------------------------------------------------------------
>
> Holt is doin' his thang up in tha' studio at KZSU and will be
> joined by j.phlip of dirtybird records, dotbleep, and nightlight
> music.
>
> J.Phlip, known to most as Jess or Jessica Rose Phillippe. She was
> completely ruined when she discovered house music in her hometown of
> Champaign, IL just 2 hours south of Chicago. This location might
> help describe the how or why behind this unique genre bending blend
> that Phlip brings to the dancefloor. Perhaps it was the proximity to
> Chicago that let house music make its influence, but the distance
> that allowed her the freedom to eventually welcome other sounds into
> her mix. Her sets posses this fun lets-not-forget-this-is-dance-music
> feeling and simultaneously keeps you guessing as to what might come
> next. Her collection spans house, tech house, deep house, techno,
> random bleeps, and special bloops.
>
> In 2005 she won 'Beauty and the Beats', a national DJ competition
> help by BPM magazine, that lead to a tour with DJ Rap, Colette, and
> Reid Speed. Since then she has made a name for herself as a DJ in
> Chicago and now as DJ-slash-Producer in San Francisco.
>
> On her first release for dirtybird, "J" has created a track that is
> both intricate and massive. A wall of devastating bass anchors
> Rumble Rumble's assault, bolstered by an effervescent rhythmic net
> of popcorn snaps, soda cans popping open, and seductive whispers and
> giggles at the very edge of audibility. She has been a pivotal part
> of Chicago's electronic music community for many years and has since
> secured a residency at San Francisco's infamous Endup nightclub that
> is notoriously know for non-stop never-ending parties. Look out for
> J.Phlip's upcoming releases on Dotbleep, Alland Byallo's Nightlight
> Music, and of course more Dirtybird!
>
> BLAH BLAH BLAH BLAH.... and she needs to clean her room...
>
> oh lord and she SRSLY needs to do her laundry...
>
> You can download her promo mixes and find out more about her upcoming
> events at her myspace page.
>
> Myspace:
> http://hsomusic.com/sh/35
>
> Dirtybird Records Artist page:
> http://hsomusic.com/sh/36
>
> You can find out more about Holt and his show at:
> http://hsomusic.com/
>
> Upcoming Events for Holt:
> 02/25 - Tryptich Restaurant
> 03/08 - The Rhythm Room @ The EndUp
>
> Epiphany of Sound with J.C. - Th 9AM-12PM Pacific/US
> ----------------------------------------------------
>
> After 14 years, DJ J.C.'s techno/house/electronica showcase has
> garnered much attention and devotion. Like most folks at Stanford's
> radio station, he's a volunteer, proving that his motivation isn't
> a paycheck; it's his passion to share his interest in one of music's
> most eclectic genres. With his conversational style, inclusion of
> producers and musicians from both the local & international scene,
> and his stewardship of the station's 24-hour marathons during
> Solstices and Equinoxes, it's no wonder that DJ J.C has made a
> connection with listeners in a very crowded market. Catch his live
> broadcasts or listen to the previous week's program at underheard.org.
>
> J.C. will email this week if he has an update on any guests.
>
> Thanks for your support!!!
>
> --
> Holt Sorenson/Eclektronik Groove
> hso@hsomusic.com
> hsomusic.com - myspace.com/hsomusic
> KZSU (kzsulive.stanford.edu) show Th @ 6-9AM US/Pacific

On Tue, 24 Feb 2009, Ben Haus wrote:
-&e->Why not just stay until BART is running again?

Sometimes you ask a list a question and you get an amateur answer, but not 
this time.  This is a pro answer, from a pro.

THIS IS HOW WE DO IT.
andyw

p.s. You can also look into AC Transit, which has all kinds of late night 
service across the bridge.  Or you can cab it (ridiculously expensive 
unless you go with a few people).  Or make plans to crash somewhere in SF 
till the BART is running.  Or borrow a car.  Or bum a ride.  Or rent a 
hotel room in SF.  Or ask your parents to pick you up.

The Flaming Lotus Girls and The Ambient Mafia present:
SERPENT MOTHER ART RECEPTION  *  SATURDAY, 03.07.09

On Saturday March 7th, the Serpent will light up the Bay in an art opening =
gala reception from 7.00PM-midnight.

There has never been a sculpture like the Serpent Mother. The warmth of her=
 embrace and her coiling design create an atmospheric space in which over a=
 thousand people can stand. Her 168=E2=80=99 long stainless steel spine coi=
ls around the massive space, while her 20=E2=80=99 long neck and head tower=
 over her audience. The audience takes control, however, by directing her m=
ovement, raising her hydraulically- actuated neck and opening her fanged mo=
uth. Full audience participation makes each installation a singular experie=
nce =E2=80=93 come make it happen.

This magnificent installation of a 168' skeletal stainless steel snake will=
 be on display Saturday March 7th, on Treasure Island. We will open the Ser=
pent for a gallery opening from 7 pm until midnight. We hope you will join =
us for this fun and free event.

Music provided by The Ambient Mafia:
olde nasty vs. peek nasty
the captain vs. harken
shane
mino
redstickman

About the FLG:
The Flaming Lotus Girls are a female-driven group of metal artists who desi=
gn and construct kinetic, mechanical fire art. Our mission is to create mon=
umental works of interactive art through a collaborative process. Our visio=
n is to empower women to learn new skills and become experienced, talented =
and active artists in their own right.

Our work =E2=80=93 a combination of sculptural arts, kinetics, robotics, el=
ectronics, and fire engineering - is designed collaboratively; made collabo=
ratively.

We create interactive large-scale fire installations that engages viewers a=
nd invite them to become part of the art.

Saturday, 3/7/09

Treasure Island, SF

Well considering how traffic has dropped like a brick here, this is the
busiest thread SFR has seen in over 3 months, it might be cool to figure out
if the kid is being sincere or not before throwing out innuendos and not so
subtle slams.

With Apollo gone we've lost one end of the spectrum and it can't hurt for
the scene, as it were, to refresh itself with new blood and jumping
somebody's shit before they've established their bona fides might not be the
most attractive way to go about it.

I'm just sayin'.

How old was Brian Behlendorf when he set this hub up?

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help


ok - some "nice" advice:

1) join bayraves:  not many under 18 parties are posted here.

2) go down telegraph.  you live in berkeley, you should know where that is.  pick up some flyers.  check the age limit.  berkeley parties will probably have flyers in berkeley more than SF, so you have the jump on the underground tip in your city.

3) get a friend to drive you to/from the party.  if you don't have friends, hang out around telegraph and make some.

4) DIY.  really - if there aren't any parties in your area, throw one.  DJs are always willing to play for free if you are sincere and have a good heart behind what you're trying to do.

From: michael the redstickman <red_stickman@yahoo.com>

ok - some "nice" advice:

1) join bayraves:  not many under 18 parties are posted here.

2) go down telegraph.  you live in berkeley, you should know where that is.  pick up some flyers.  check the age limit.  berkeley parties will probably have flyers in berkeley more than SF, so you have the jump on the underground tip in your city.

3) get a friend to drive you to/from the party.  if you don't have friends, hang out around telegraph and make some.

4) DIY.  really - if there aren't any parties in your area, throw one.  DJs are always willing to play for free if you are sincere and have a good heart behind what you're trying to do.

> ok - some "nice" advice:
>
> 1) join bayraves:  not many under 18 parties are posted here.
>
> 2) go down telegraph.  you live in berkeley, you should know where that is.
>  pick up some flyers.  check the age limit.  berkeley parties will probably
> have flyers in berkeley more than SF, so you have the jump on the
> underground tip in your city.
>
> 3) get a friend to drive you to/from the party.  if you don't have friends,
> hang out around telegraph and make some.
>
> 4) DIY.  really - if there aren't any parties in your area, throw one.  DJs
> are always willing to play for free if you are sincere and have a good heart
> behind what you're trying to do.
>

A good way to earn your cred around here is to share information about yourself.

1. Start with the music.  Who are your favorite artists?  What genres do you like?  Why?
2. How did you get into electronic music?  When? Where? Why?
3. Pen spinning?  Please explain.
4. Berkeley? I assume you a BHS student.  Who is your favorite teacher?

No one cares if you are 17 or 107, if you are intelligent, interested in the music, and not an irresponsible dumb ass.

Peter

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help

some background for you on what is rave. i kind of wish i had wikipedia 
when i was getting into raves. i spent untold hours on boards and lists 
like this conversing with techno heads around the world in 
alt.music.techno to get a feel for what is really going on in newsgroups 
way back when.

fortunately for our friend (who's chosen e-mail name bears a striking 
resemblance to a new york hiphop mixtape icon) wikipedia is here to stay 
as the world collective consciousness:

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rave

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Techno
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electro_(music)
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_music/History_of_House_Music
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PLUR

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KLF
learn to love the absurdity and awesomeness of the JAMs
http://www.klf-communications.net/

and here are some fun sites that i like that may help you get more 
familiar with the music and culture:

http://fusionanomaly.net/
this site is a mega spiral with an emphasis on psytrance culture. love it.

online publications:
http://www.xlr8r.com/
these guys used to be the shit but are a bunch of punks now.. but they 
are still on the cutting edge, admittedly. they still owe me an original 
playstation from a contest i won yeeears ago. am i bitter? maybe. lol. 
if you guys feel like buying me a PS3, all is forgiven.

http://www.bpmmagazine.net/
still good, always a bit 'bosh' though.

http://emusician.com/
always just a little ahead of the game.

http://remixmag.com/
a dj friendly publication, always a fun read. mostly for djs and remixers.

http://residentadvisor.net
mentioned this one before but its a pretty important one.

music related searches and buying sources:
http://www.last.fm/
http://www.nuloop.com/en/
http://www.dancerecords.com/
http://www.beatport.com/
http://songza.com/
http://gemm.com/
http://www.discogs.com/
http://boomkat.com/

gotta give props to:
http://hyperreal.org/
its why we're here today. http://hyperreal.org/info/history.html

http://www.youtube.com
is also a great source for historical references to EDM. just type in an 
artist you might be interested in.

and lastly, my little site that could:
http://www.defsf.com

i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music and 
raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and 
everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything is 
online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this worldwide 
scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just find 
information about undergrounds and club culture, buy cheap tracks and 
follow any dj anywhere in the world. its a fantastic completely open 
secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are always here with 
welcoming arms for those willing to embrace our culture. i'm sure you 
will find that rave is not just a scene its a lifestyle choice that 
shares a similarity to punk.

i hope you find your knit anthony, and you are welcome to ask me any 
questions as long they are about the culture and getting in touch with 
what is real about the scene and your responsible role within it. be 
courteous and open-minded and all will be apparent.

respect,
sean.

From: sean ocean [mailto:seanocean@defsf.com]=20
