Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help

some background for you on what is rave. i kind of wish i had wikipedia=20
when i was getting into raves. i spent untold hours on boards and lists=20
like this conversing with techno heads around the world in=20
alt.music.techno to get a feel for what is really going on in newsgroups

way back when.

fortunately for our friend (who's chosen e-mail name bears a striking=20
resemblance to a new york hiphop mixtape icon) wikipedia is here to stay

as the world collective consciousness:

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rave

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Techno
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electro_(music)
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_music/History_of_House_Music
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PLUR

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KLF
learn to love the absurdity and awesomeness of the JAMs
http://www.klf-communications.net/

and here are some fun sites that i like that may help you get more=20
familiar with the music and culture:

http://fusionanomaly.net/
this site is a mega spiral with an emphasis on psytrance culture. love
it.

online publications:
http://www.xlr8r.com/
these guys used to be the shit but are a bunch of punks now.. but they=20
are still on the cutting edge, admittedly. they still owe me an original

playstation from a contest i won yeeears ago. am i bitter? maybe. lol.=20
if you guys feel like buying me a PS3, all is forgiven.

http://www.bpmmagazine.net/
still good, always a bit 'bosh' though.

http://emusician.com/
always just a little ahead of the game.

http://remixmag.com/
a dj friendly publication, always a fun read. mostly for djs and
remixers.

http://residentadvisor.net
mentioned this one before but its a pretty important one.

music related searches and buying sources:
http://www.last.fm/
http://www.nuloop.com/en/
http://www.dancerecords.com/
http://www.beatport.com/
http://songza.com/
http://gemm.com/
http://www.discogs.com/
http://boomkat.com/

gotta give props to:
http://hyperreal.org/
its why we're here today. http://hyperreal.org/info/history.html

http://www.youtube.com
is also a great source for historical references to EDM. just type in an

artist you might be interested in.

and lastly, my little site that could:
http://www.defsf.com

i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music and

raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and=20
everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything is=20
online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this worldwide

scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just find=20
information about undergrounds and club culture, buy cheap tracks and=20
follow any dj anywhere in the world. its a fantastic completely open=20
secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are always here with=20
welcoming arms for those willing to embrace our culture. i'm sure you=20
will find that rave is not just a scene its a lifestyle choice that=20
shares a similarity to punk.

i hope you find your knit anthony, and you are welcome to ask me any=20
questions as long they are about the culture and getting in touch with=20
what is real about the scene and your responsible role within it. be=20
courteous and open-minded and all will be apparent.

respect,
sean.

that guy has been known to provide a biased slant. i wanted the lad to 
learn on his own and form his own opinions based on what he found. 
though the tiesto comic is still a classic if you have that.

this guide takes me back to some cool trance i used to listen to like 
lazonby.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kPYO-gkqtrE

remember when people in electronic music tried really really hard and 
indy labels had to kiss ass to Sire and TVT? maybe beatport isn't so 
good for putting out music..? the ubiquity of fast cheap and dirty 
distro cheapens the music i think. maybe if more people had the 
mentality that they had to compete with major labels they would try 
harder. i think when i first saw the lazonby sleeve i came to this 
conclusion like a way long time ago. he had his image up there like he 
was front 242 or something. lol. baby ford also verified this conclusion 
to me when i asked myself why 1992 was sucha  great year for electronic 
music.. BFORD9 was put out on sire which put out Yaz(oo) and Depeche 
Mode which went on to be eaten up by WEA.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qbqrg6-XmsI

>> everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely
>> everything is

>> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you

>> secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are
>> always here with

>> will find that rave is not just a scene its a lifestyle
>> choice that 
>> shares a similarity to punk.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help

I have to say this is the single thread where I've read every message  
in, oh, 6 months? maybe more? I've been lurking on this list for maybe  
3 years, since I moved here, and have actually only been to one EDM  
event in that time period. But this thread, for a variety of reasons,  
makes me a little excited again. It has a little to do with the snark,  
to be honest, because it reminds me of good old nw-raves, where I cut  
my very own teeth and made friends. It has a little to do with the  
links being shared because it makes me feel like I know what I'm  
talking about again, even though I totally don't - and haven't for at  
least 6 years. And it has a little to do with the earnest responses  
given to a seemingly genuine kid with questions.

Ahh, to be a raver again. So, my interest is piqued! Keep me reading!  
Get me involved! I've got time and energy to give, but not so many  
skills or connections.

Hi everyone, I'm Colleen. Once upon a time, I was active up in  
Seattle. That was 10 years ago. Now I am not that old and out of  
touch. Bring me back into the fray?

Colleen

>
> some background for you on what is rave. i kind of wish i had  
> wikipedia
> when i was getting into raves. i spent untold hours on boards and  
> lists
> like this conversing with techno heads around the world in
> alt.music.techno to get a feel for what is really going on in  
> newsgroups
>
> way back when.
>
> fortunately for our friend (who's chosen e-mail name bears a striking
> resemblance to a new york hiphop mixtape icon) wikipedia is here to  
> stay
>
> as the world collective consciousness:
>
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rave
>
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Techno
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electro_(music)
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_music/History_of_House_Music
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PLUR
>
> http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KLF
> learn to love the absurdity and awesomeness of the JAMs
> http://www.klf-communications.net/
>
> and here are some fun sites that i like that may help you get more
> familiar with the music and culture:
>
> http://fusionanomaly.net/
> this site is a mega spiral with an emphasis on psytrance culture. love
> it.
>
> online publications:
> http://www.xlr8r.com/
> these guys used to be the shit but are a bunch of punks now.. but they
> are still on the cutting edge, admittedly. they still owe me an  
> original
>
> playstation from a contest i won yeeears ago. am i bitter? maybe. lol.
> if you guys feel like buying me a PS3, all is forgiven.
>
> http://www.bpmmagazine.net/
> still good, always a bit 'bosh' though.
>
> http://emusician.com/
> always just a little ahead of the game.
>
> http://remixmag.com/
> a dj friendly publication, always a fun read. mostly for djs and
> remixers.
>
> http://residentadvisor.net
> mentioned this one before but its a pretty important one.
>
> music related searches and buying sources:
> http://www.last.fm/
> http://www.nuloop.com/en/
> http://www.dancerecords.com/
> http://www.beatport.com/
> http://songza.com/
> http://gemm.com/
> http://www.discogs.com/
> http://boomkat.com/
>
> gotta give props to:
> http://hyperreal.org/
> its why we're here today. http://hyperreal.org/info/history.html
>
> http://www.youtube.com
> is also a great source for historical references to EDM. just type  
> in an
>
> artist you might be interested in.
>
> and lastly, my little site that could:
> http://www.defsf.com
>
> i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music  
> and
>
> raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and
> everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything  
> is
> online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this  
> worldwide
>
> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just  
> find
> information about undergrounds and club culture, buy cheap tracks and
> follow any dj anywhere in the world. its a fantastic completely open
> secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are always here with
> welcoming arms for those willing to embrace our culture. i'm sure you
> will find that rave is not just a scene its a lifestyle choice that
> shares a similarity to punk.
>
> i hope you find your knit anthony, and you are welcome to ask me any
> questions as long they are about the culture and getting in touch with
> what is real about the scene and your responsible role within it. be
> courteous and open-minded and all will be apparent.
>
> respect,
> sean.

> A good way to earn your cred around here is to share information about yourself.
>
> 1. Start with the music.  Who are your favorite artists?  What genres do you like?  Why?
> 2. How did you get into electronic music?  When? Where? Why?
> 3. Pen spinning?  Please explain.
> 4. Berkeley? I assume you a BHS student.  Who is your favorite teacher?
>
> No one cares if you are 17 or 107, if you are intelligent, interested in the music, and not an irresponsible dumb ass.
>
> Peter

>> http://www.xlr8r.com/

>> playstation from a contest i won yeeears ago. am i bitter? maybe. lol.

>> a dj friendly publication, always a fun read. mostly for djs and
>> remixers.

>> and lastly, my little site that could:
>> http://www.defsf.com

>> i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music and
>>
>> raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and
>> everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything is
>> online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this worldwide
>>
>> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just find
>> information about undergrounds and club culture, buy cheap tracks and
>> follow any dj anywhere in the world. its a fantastic completely open
>> secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are always here with

>> shares a similarity to punk.

This is the most active thread SFR has seen in at least 6 mos, if not
longer.

Not bad for a kid that's new to the scene, even if everyone let their
paranoid post RAVE Act II paranoia get the better of them and defaulted to
snarkily jumping his shit to start.

Sean, not only did you leave out Ishkur in that pretty thorough and
comprehensive list of yours, but Apollo has got something to say too
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Also, judging by the traffic this thread has generated I'd say Tony just
gave us all a lesson in DIY.

Throwing  TAZ out there with no other data points is just mean.

Short version, TAZ, 'Temporary Autonomous Zone' is an modern updating of
Aleister Crowley's dictum:

'Do What Thou Wilt Shall Be The Whole Of The Law'.

In simplest, non-academic terms, it is a theory of personal liberty that
gets tested out at every party.

Here's the wiki http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone and
the full book itself http://www.hermetic.com/bey/taz_cont.html

Here's the Tiesto comic in the same spot it's been since forever
http://farmer-glitch.blogspot.com/2005/11/aha-aha.html

One thing about this thread I really like is that it *totally* confirms that
I'm doing the right thing in moving to Germany this Saturday, since, well
they not only have DJs spin *inside* the motehrfucking McDonalds there,
(check out the DJ's Burberry record bag), but they turn over *entire* cities
for a party http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bpO-xXWqk0E

That was just one night in Dresden, I can just imagine what a huge city like
Berlin is like during the Love Parade when 2 million partiers descend on the
city for a better part of a week, with full government and business support.

This shit we have here in the States with SWAT Teams and Apache Helicopters
breaking up parties, (and a meager turn out of 50k ppl, in a Nation of 300
mil ppl, that has to be held out in a remote desert location because it
would be too disruptive to mainstream American Monday Night Football/Must
See NBC TV life), is sad, weak and pathetic, and speaks to a genuine lack of
personal freedom here in the good old US of A.

YMMV.

I hope to take a side trip to Ibiza in the next few months to see how it's
really done instead of this being treated like backwards children garbage we
tolerate in the US.

....

>> i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music and

>> raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and
>> everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything is
>> online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this worldwide
>>
>> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just find

>> shares a similarity to punk.

--- On Thu, 2/26/09, Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com> wrote:
From: Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help
To: "Colleen McGarry" <colleen@grenadine.org>
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Date: Thursday, February 26, 2009, 1:27 AM

This is the most active thread SFR has seen in at least 6 mos, if not
longer.

Not bad for a kid that's new to the scene, even if everyone let their
paranoid post RAVE Act II paranoia get the better of them and defaulted to
snarkily jumping his shit to start.

Sean, not only did you leave out Ishkur in that pretty thorough and
comprehensive list of yours, but Apollo has got something to say too
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Also, judging by the traffic this thread has generated I'd say Tony just
gave us all a lesson in DIY.

Throwing  TAZ out there with no other data points is just mean.

Short version, TAZ, 'Temporary Autonomous Zone' is an modern updating
of
Aleister Crowley's dictum:

'Do What Thou Wilt Shall Be The Whole Of The Law'.

In simplest, non-academic terms, it is a theory of personal liberty that
gets tested out at every party.

Here's the wiki http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone and
the full book itself http://www.hermetic.com/bey/taz_cont.html

Here's the Tiesto comic in the same spot it's been since forever
http://farmer-glitch.blogspot.com/2005/11/aha-aha.html

One thing about this thread I really like is that it *totally* confirms that
I'm doing the right thing in moving to Germany this Saturday, since, well
they not only have DJs spin *inside* the motehrfucking McDonalds there,
(check out the DJ's Burberry record bag), but they turn over *entire*
cities
for a party http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bpO-xXWqk0E

That was just one night in Dresden, I can just imagine what a huge city like
Berlin is like during the Love Parade when 2 million partiers descend on the
city for a better part of a week, with full government and business support.

This shit we have here in the States with SWAT Teams and Apache Helicopters
breaking up parties, (and a meager turn out of 50k ppl, in a Nation of 300
mil ppl, that has to be held out in a remote desert location because it
would be too disruptive to mainstream American Monday Night Football/Must
See NBC TV life), is sad, weak and pathetic, and speaks to a genuine lack of
personal freedom here in the good old US of A.

YMMV.

I hope to take a side trip to Ibiza in the next few months to see how it's
really done instead of this being treated like backwards children garbage we
tolerate in the US.

.....

is

worldwide
>>
>> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just

I would tell my parents I am staying at this friends house.
And then we would go to the party and I would take a shower at whos ever ho=
use I crashed at after the party.=20
=A0
My mom drove me to my first party in San Fancisco. May 24th 1996 Space Chil=
dren threw a party called Open Space at this building near Market that had =
hardwood floors. The map point was at F8 on Haight and the ticket was a whi=
te feather.
I dont remember the whole line up but I know that Carlos was spinning so wa=
s Moshe.
My mom drove me to the map point and then to the party and then I called he=
r to pick me up when I was ready to leave.
=A0
One time I brought my mom to a party because we were throwing it and she di=
dnt lock her car door and someone stole her car. So she called the cops and=
 then they saw that there were people up in the dance studio and they broke=
 the party up. I was really upset about that. This was Wonder back in 1998.=
 In the dance studio they kept trying to sneak everyone in the party into t=
he extra room and pretend like no one was there.
=A0
I remember there was some party in Berkley at the Casa Z=A0and that I had n=
o ride or money to go so I posted on Here and this=A0awsome=A0chick from SF=
R=A0called me and said she would give me a ride and then when I got to the =
party somehow I didnt hafto pay which was sweet.
Yeah, but that party was cool.
=A0
I remember the parties at the Cyborganics location. Lepidoptera 2 was one o=
f those parties. I have that on video tape somewhere.=A0I remember Amanda a=
nd Dustin's wedding at Cyborganics. I remember a Happy Kids party at Cyborg=
anics too.=A0 Those were great because I could just walk to the party from =
my moms or take the bus. I think that was really awsome when my mom lived i=
n SF near all these different locations. Why did she hafto move?=20
=A0
I remember this one time that I made a pair of fur pants and they were yell=
ow and orange and I had lots of candy gear on and I took the BART from SF t=
o Oakland to go to a party at 2nd and Jackson and my friend Brian and I are=
 walking down the street in Oakland and these two ladies come out of this c=
hicken wing reastaurant and look at us and are like "Oh no Shaquanda! I see=
n these people on Jenny Jones!" "You're like club kids" And I was like uh-o=
h and so we just ran all the way to 2nd and Jackson.=20
=A0
I remember the 3 Day Harmony/ASR Camp Out. That was fuckin awsome.
I have that on video some where.
=A0
I remember a Gathering party up at Angel's Camp where in the day this guy o=
verdosed on GHB and they had to fly a helicopter in with paramedics to resc=
ue him. And then the guys wakes up all of a sudden and said "what happened =
to the music?"
=A0
I remember this party way back in the day at Home Base where it was raining=
 and they had all those stand up heaters to keep people warm and as we were=
 leaving the party we see a little pile of clothes on the ground and there =
is like a pair of shoes and then some socks and we kept on walking towards =
the parking lot and then we saw a pair of pants and then a shirt and all of=
 a sudden there is a naked guy standing there going "Why Is It So Cold??"
=A0
=A0

From: Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>

This is the most active thread SFR has seen in at least 6 mos, if not
longer.

Not bad for a kid that's new to the scene, even if everyone let their
paranoid post RAVE Act II paranoia get the better of them and defaulted to
snarkily jumping his shit to start.

Sean, not only did you leave out Ishkur in that pretty thorough and
comprehensive list of yours, but Apollo has got something to say too
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Also, judging by the traffic this thread has generated I'd say Tony just
gave us all a lesson in DIY.

Throwing=A0 TAZ out there with no other data points is just mean.

Short version, TAZ, 'Temporary Autonomous Zone' is an modern updating
of
Aleister Crowley's dictum:

'Do What Thou Wilt Shall Be The Whole Of The Law'.

In simplest, non-academic terms, it is a theory of personal liberty that
gets tested out at every party.

Here's the wiki http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone and
the full book itself http://www.hermetic.com/bey/taz_cont.html

Here's the Tiesto comic in the same spot it's been since forever
http://farmer-glitch.blogspot.com/2005/11/aha-aha.html

One thing about this thread I really like is that it *totally* confirms tha=
t
I'm doing the right thing in moving to Germany this Saturday, since, well
they not only have DJs spin *inside* the motehrfucking McDonalds there,
(check out the DJ's Burberry record bag), but they turn over *entire*
cities
for a party http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3DbpO-xXWqk0E

That was just one night in Dresden, I can just imagine what a huge city lik=
e
Berlin is like during the Love Parade when 2 million partiers descend on th=
e
city for a better part of a week, with full government and business support=
..

This shit we have here in the States with SWAT Teams and Apache Helicopters
breaking up parties, (and a meager turn out of 50k ppl, in a Nation of 300
mil ppl, that has to be held out in a remote desert location because it
would be too disruptive to mainstream American Monday Night Football/Must
See NBC TV life), is sad, weak and pathetic, and speaks to a genuine lack o=
f
personal freedom here in the good old US of A.

YMMV.

I hope to take a side trip to Ibiza in the next few months to see how it's
really done instead of this being treated like backwards children garbage w=
e
tolerate in the US.

......

----- Original Message ----
From: Paul Simcovich-Hayden <paulewogsf@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org; tonytouch510@yahoo.com
Sent: Thursday, February 26, 2009 5:36:36 AM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help

I would tell my parents I am staying at this friends house.
And then we would go to the party and I would take a shower at whos ever house I crashed at after the party. 
 
My mom drove me to my first party in San Fancisco. May 24th 1996Classic posting. Space Children threw a party called Open Space at this building near Market that had hardwood floors. The map point was at F8 on Haight and the ticket was a white feather.
I dont remember the whole line up but I know that Carlos was spinning so was Moshe.
My mom drove me to the map point and then to the party and then I called her to pick me up when I was ready to leave.
 
One time I brought my mom to a party because we were throwing it and she didnt lock her car door and someone stole her car. So she called the cops and then they saw that there were people up in the dance studio and they broke the party up. I was really upset about that. This was Wonder back in 1998. In the dance studio they kept trying to sneak everyone in the party into the extra room and pretend like no one was there.
 
I remember there was some party in Berkley at the Casa Z and that I had no ride or money to go so I posted on Here and this awsome chick from SFR called me and said she would give me a ride and then when I got to the party somehow I didnt hafto pay which was sweet.
Yeah, but that party was cool.
 
I remember the parties at the Cyborganics location. Lepidoptera 2 was one of those parties. I have that on video tape somewhere. I remember Amanda and Dustin's wedding at Cyborganics. I remember a Happy Kids party at Cyborganics too.  Those were great because I could just walk to the party from my moms or take the bus. I think that was really awsome when my mom lived in SF near all these different locations. Why did she hafto move? 
 
I remember this one time that I made a pair of fur pants and they were yellow and orange and I had lots of candy gear on and I took the BART from SF to Oakland to go to a party at 2nd and Jackson and my friend Brian and I are walking down the street in Oakland and these two ladies come out of this chicken wing reastaurant and look at us and are like "Oh no Shaquanda! I seen these people on Jenny Jones!" "You're like club kids" And I was like uh-oh and so we just ran all the way to 2nd and Jackson. 
 
I remember the 3 Day Harmony/ASR Camp Out. That was fuckin awsome.
I have that on video some where.
 
I remember a Gathering party up at Angel's Camp where in the day this guy overdosed on GHB and they had to fly a helicopter in with paramedics to rescue him. And then the guys wakes up all of a sudden and said "what happened to the music?"
 
I remember this party way back in the day at Home Base where it was raining and they had all those stand up heaters to keep people warm and as we were leaving the party we see a little pile of clothes on the ground and there is like a pair of shoes and then some socks and we kept on walking towards the parking lot and then we saw a pair of pants and then a shirt and all of a sudden there is a naked guy standing there going "Why Is It So Cold??"

--- On Thu, 2/26/09, Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com> wrote:
From: Nyc Labrets <digitalcomponents@gmail.com>
Subject: Re: [sfraves] RE: Need some help
To: "Colleen McGarry" <colleen@grenadine.org>
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Date: Thursday, February 26, 2009, 1:27 AM

This is the most active thread SFR has seen in at least 6 mos, if not
longer.

Not bad for a kid that's new to the scene, even if everyone let their
paranoid post RAVE Act II paranoia get the better of them and defaulted to
snarkily jumping his shit to start.

Sean, not only did you leave out Ishkur in that pretty thorough and
comprehensive list of yours, but Apollo has got something to say too
http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

Also, judging by the traffic this thread has generated I'd say Tony just
gave us all a lesson in DIY.

Throwing  TAZ out there with no other data points is just mean.

Short version, TAZ, 'Temporary Autonomous Zone' is an modern updating
of
Aleister Crowley's dictum:

'Do What Thou Wilt Shall Be The Whole Of The Law'.

In simplest, non-academic terms, it is a theory of personal liberty that
gets tested out at every party.

Here's the wiki http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporary_Autonomous_Zone and
the full book itself http://www.hermetic.com/bey/taz_cont.html

Here's the Tiesto comic in the same spot it's been since forever
http://farmer-glitch.blogspot.com/2005/11/aha-aha.html

One thing about this thread I really like is that it *totally* confirms that
I'm doing the right thing in moving to Germany this Saturday, since, well
they not only have DJs spin *inside* the motehrfucking McDonalds there,
(check out the DJ's Burberry record bag), but they turn over *entire*
cities
for a party http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bpO-xXWqk0E

That was just one night in Dresden, I can just imagine what a huge city like
Berlin is like during the Love Parade when 2 million partiers descend on the
city for a better part of a week, with full government and business support..

This shit we have here in the States with SWAT Teams and Apache Helicopters
breaking up parties, (and a meager turn out of 50k ppl, in a Nation of 300
mil ppl, that has to be held out in a remote desert location because it
would be too disruptive to mainstream American Monday Night Football/Must
See NBC TV life), is sad, weak and pathetic, and speaks to a genuine lack of
personal freedom here in the good old US of A.

YMMV.

I hope to take a side trip to Ibiza in the next few months to see how it's
really done instead of this being treated like backwards children garbage we
tolerate in the US.

......

>> playstation from a contest i won yeeears ago. am i bitter? maybe. lol.

>> i feel like this is a great time to be getting into electronic music
and
>>
>> raves. there are so many directions for the EDM scene to go in and
>> everything is fresh again. especially now that absolutely everything
is
>> online now. its easier to just get wired up and all up in this
worldwide
>>
>> scene in a hurry. no matter where you go in the world you can just
find
>> information about undergrounds and club culture, buy cheap tracks and
>> follow any dj anywhere in the world. its a fantastic completely open
>> secret. if people want to know, they will. and we are always here with
>> welcoming arms for those willing to embrace our culture. i'm sure
you
>> will find that rave is not just a scene its a lifestyle choice that
>> shares a similarity to punk.
>>
>> i hope you find your knit anthony, and you are welcome to ask me any
>> questions as long they are about the culture and getting in touch with
>> what is real about the scene and your responsible role within it. be
>> courteous and open-minded and all will be apparent.

>> sean.

ou can do too!=20

so=0Ayou can see why i love this night right? i mean, half of you make=0Amu=
